<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cemented Yangtze Breach Holding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JIUJIANG, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Yangtze River breach at
Jiujiang in east China's Jiangxi Province remains effective since
being cemented together yesterday afternoon, according to the
latest reports.
</P>
<P>
The newly repaired embankment is some 1.2 meters higher than
the Yangtze water level, which dropped to 22.62 meters at 8 pm
this evening, 0.06 meters lower than at the same time Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Many soldiers and civilians are still working to further
fortify the trapezium-shaped cemented breach, 4 meters wide on
top, 25 meters at the base, and nearly 100 meters long, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The water flow rate at the breach was 400 cubic meters per
second on Friday when the embankment was torn, but now there is
only some seeping.
</P>
<P>
Experts are now working to wipe out the seepage completely, and
expect this to be accomplished in three days.
</P>
<P>
However, receding floodwaters may easily cause embankment
collapses and landslides, so greater efforts are urgently needed
to keep alert for any possible weak point along the Yangtze dikes,
experts warned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
