<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Denies Involvement in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Thursday denied its
involvement in the Islamic Taliban's recent military offensives
against their rivals in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"We categorically reject allegations of Pakistan's involvement
in the current situation in Afghanistan," the Foreign Office said
in a press release Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
"It is regrettable that the government-controlled print and
electronic media in some countries have been utilized in an
orchestrated campaign of vilification against Pakistan," it said.
</P>
<P>
"It is a lesson of history that the Afghans have never
tolerated outside interference in their internal affairs," it
said, adding that Pakistan considers the military fortunes or
misfortunes of any particular group or faction as purely an
internal affair of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"It is our earnest hope that the countries sharing borders with
Afghanistan, instead of raising alarms over a non-existent threat
will join Pakistan in promoting peace and harmony in that
beleaguered country," it said.
</P>
<P>
"Throughout the Afghan conflict, Pakistan has followed a
principled, upright and transparent policy," it said.
</P>
<P>
"It has offered its fullest cooperation and has supported all
efforts including those of the U.N. and the Organization of the
Islamic Conference to bring peace to Afghanistan. We shall remain
steadfast to this policy," it said.
</P>
<P>
In their latest attempt to take over the whole Afghanistan, the
hard-line Taliban militia on Saturday overran Mazar-e-Sharif,
headquarters of the rival Northern Alliance.
</P>
<P>
Then they proceeded to take Taloqan, a strategic base of the
opposition alliance in Takhar Province, on Tuesday, and
Pul-i-Khumri and Nahrin in Baghlan Province on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Russia, Iran and the Afghan opposition have accused Pakistan of
giving military aid to the Taliban. 
</P>
</TEXT>
