<HEADLINE> Lesotho Ruling, Opposition Party Supporters Clash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Members of the ruling
Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD) and opposition party
supporters clashed outside King Letsie III's palace in Maseru
Thursday, South African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted police spokesman Sekoateng Serabeli as saying that
about 1,000 LCD members marched at 3 p.m. (1300 GMT) to the
palace, where hundreds of opposition party members have camped
since last Tuesday in protest against the May general election
results.
</P>
<P>
Serabeli said fighting erupted when the LCD members confronted
the protesters.
</P>
<P>
"After a while LCD supporters ran away and gunshots were
heard, but it is not yet known who fired them," Serabeli said.
</P>
<P>
There were unconfirmed reports that two people were shot.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted an unnamed palace source as saying that Letsie was
deeply worried about the unrest.
</P>
<P>
"The king is deeply worried, unfortunately he cannot take
sides," said the source.
</P>
<P>
"The constitution does not allow him to intervene. He cannot
take sides."
</P>
<P>
Opposition party members claim that the election was rigged in
favor of the LCD, which took 79 of 80 seats in the National
Assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
