<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Retail Sales Decline in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- A large drop in auto sales
caused by the General Motors strike in July produced the worst
decline in retail sales in 15 months, the Commerce Department
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales plunged 0.4 percent from the previous month, to a
seasonally adjusted 224.7 billion U.S. dollars, after rising just
0.1 percent in June, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
Auto sales dropped 3 percent, to 59 billion dollars, also the
worst decrease since April 1997. Except the auto sales, all other
retail goods picked up 0.5 percent as compared with a 0.1 percent
dip in June, in line with the average so far this year.
</P>
<P>
In July, sales of big-ticket durable goods thrived. Furniture
stores reported a 1.2 percent increase and building-supply and
hardware stores, 1.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Sales rose 0.7 percent at clothing and accessory shops, 0.6
percent at drug stores, 0.4 percent at gas stations, 0.3 percent
at food stores and 0.2 percent at department stores. However, they
fell 0.4 percent at restaurants and bars.
</P>
<P>
In another separate report released here Thursday, the Labor
Department said the number of Americans filing first-time
applications for unemployment benefits slipped by 7,000 last week
to a seasonally adjusted 301,000.
</P>
<P>
That was down from 394,000 for two consecutive weeks in late
June and early July, when tens of thousands of GM strikers filed
claims.
</P>
<P>
However, consumers have continued spending briskly because jobs
remain plentiful and income is rising and because, even with
recent drops, stock portfolios reflect large accumulated gains.
</P>
</TEXT>
