<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1530 GMT, August 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO -- Rebels of the Liberation Tigers of the Tamil Eelam
(LTTE) hijacked a foreign merchant ship off the northeastern coast
of Sri Lanka Friday, according to informed sources here.
</P>
<P>
The sources said gunmen from the LTTE seized a Dubai-owned
merchant vessel with 21 crew members on board, including 16 Indian
 nationals.
</P>
<P>
The 6,000-ton ship was on its way to the northern peninsula of
Jaffna from Colombo. The ship was carrying cement and general
cargo for traders in Jaffna city.
</P>
<P>
According to Indian diplomats here, they were in contact with
the Sri Lankan military authorities and the International
Committee of the Red Cross on the fate of the crew members. But
so far there have been no details of the rebel attack. (Sri
Lanka-Rebles-Ship)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
YANGON -- The Myanmar authorities Friday deported 18 foreigners
in mitigation of their sentences passed by a district special
court, according to an order issued by the Ministry of Home
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The 18 foreigners, charged with attempting to incite unrest in
the country, were sentenced earlier on the same day by the special
court to five years' imprisonment and was later released and
deported after their punishment was commuted.
</P>
<P>
The 18 foreigners, including six Americans, three Indonesians,
three Malaysians, three Thais, two Filipinos and one Australian,
were caught and detained by the authorities on last Sunday while
reportedly distributing smuggled leaflets in downtown Yangon in
support of Myanmar people's struggle for human rights and
democracy. (Myanmar-Foreigners-Deportation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin denied on Friday that
the ruble will devalue because of the unrest on financial market,
the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"I can firmly and clearly state that ruble will not devalue.
I'm not making up the thing. All the calculations have been done.
</P>
<P>
"Work on controlling the financial situation is being conducted
every day and night, and the situation is completely under
control," Yeltsin said on arrival in Novgorod on a working visit.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that since a new wave in world financial crisis
was appearing, "we shall again make an effort to continue keeping
the situation under control."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said he will not give up the right to call an extra
session of the State Duma to discuss the stabilization draft laws,
submitted by the government.
</P>
<P>
On the Russian financial market, stocks took an unprecedented
plunge Thursday because of fallout from recent slides on other
exchanges around the globe. Most of the blue chips continued to
drop. (Russia-Yeltsin-Ruble) 
</P>
</TEXT>
