<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Recovers Remains of Nanjing Massacre Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Information Office of the
Nanjing City Government in eastern Jiangsu Province today
announced the recovery of the remains of 35 people who were proven
to be victims of the 1937 Nanjing Massacre committed by the
Japanese invaders.
</P>
<P>
The remains, which were found during excavations by the Nanjing
Jiangdongmen Museum in Nanjing earlier this year, include the
skeletons of 16 males, 7 females, 7 children and 5 which are
unidentified.
</P>
<P>
Scientific analysis shows that those people died 60 years ago,
at the time of the Nanjing Massacre. The youngest victim was 6
years old and the oldest was more than 60. Wounds and injuries
were found on some of remains.
</P>
<P>
Historical documents reveal that the area around the
Jiangdongmen Museum was used as a killing ground when the Japanese
committed the massacre in December 1937. More than 10,000 people
were killed at that time.
</P>
<P>
At today's news briefing, Qiu Ronggui, a 84-year-old survivor
of the Nanjing Massacre, denounced the crimes committed by the
Japanese invaders by telling what he saw around the Jiangdongmen
area 61 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Jiangdongmen Museum has decided to keep the remains in
order to remind people of this history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All Services at New HK Airport Return to Normal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 14 (Xinhua) -- All services at the new Hong
Kong International Airport which was commenced on July 6 this year
were approaching a high level of efficiency, the Airport Authority
said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Air Cargo Terminals Limited (HACTL), the main air
cargo franchisee, announced on Thursday its resumption of all
outbound and inbound air cargo services at the new airport.
</P>
<P>
This means that full air cargo operations are being conducted,
although HACTL will continue to process cargo at both Super
Terminal 1 at the new airport and Terminal 2 at Kai Tak, the
department said.
</P>
<P>
Partial cargo handling services were once suspended because
there appeared some problems after the new airport at Chek Lap Kok
started its operation on July 6 this year. So the Terminal 2 at
Kai Tak had to be used again.
</P>
<P>
The Airport Authority said that HACTL expects to transfer all
operations to Super Terminal 1 by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
It said that passenger services throughout the past week
continued to maintain levels of efficiency equal to or better than
at Kai Tak.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest figures given by the Airport Authority,
three quarters of flights were leaving on time or within 15
minutes of schedule. Almost all arriving passengers were clearing
immigration within 15 minutes, and the average waiting time for
their baggages was 11 minutes.
</P>
<P>
"The figures show that the new Hong Kong International Airport
is achieving levels of efficiency," said Clinton Leeks, corporate
development director of the Airport Authority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
