<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Half Asylum Seekers in UK Detained in Jail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Nearly half of asylum seekers and
immigration detainees in Britain are being held in jails rather
than at specialist detention centers, according to new figures
released Friday by the Prison Reform Trust.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half the detainees are in unsuitable conditions in jail
while detention centers are often of a poor standard, the trust
report revealed.
</P>
<P>
Prison Reform Trust director Stephen Shaw said imprisoning
asylum seekers have betrayed the "proud tradition" of the country
of helping those fleeing persecution abroad.
</P>
<P>
"By definition, a prison cannot be a suitable place to detain
someone not convicted of -- nor even suspected of -- a criminal
offense," he said.
</P>
<P>
Shaw also said sending asylum-seekers to prison was
"inappropriate, inconsistent and inhumane," and called for new
immigration detention centers to be built.
</P>
<P>
The trust report showed that in February alone, 427 asylum
seekers -- nearly half of all those in detention -- were held in
Prison Service custody.
</P>
<P>
Although the decision on whether to jail asylum seekers was
supposedly made on whether they were likely to be particularly
disruptive, in practice they were usually sent wherever there was
room.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that asylum seekers detained in prison
were likely to have less time out of their cells and fewer
opportunities for education.
</P>
<P>
They were often forced to wear "old, ill-fitting and culturally
inappropriate" clothing and suffered from inadequate communication
facilities and limited visiting rights.
</P>
<P>
The report also criticized specialist, privately-run detention
centers by highlighting their lack of adequate leisure facilities
including their libraries' poor stocks of foreign language books.
</P>
<P>
A recent White Paper on immigration and asylum said the
government was looking into ways of expanding the number of places
available outside jail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moscow Welcomes Resumed Talks Over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Friday welcomed a
decision by the ethnic Albanian leadership in Yugoslavia's
troubled province of Kosovo to resume talks with Yugoslav
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Foreign Ministry said in a news release the move is
the result of coordinated efforts by the international community,
above all the Contact Group, which stands for a political
settlement of the problem.
</P>
<P>
Russia urged Yugoslavia, Serbia and the Kosovo Albanian
community "to start negotiations immediately and without any
preliminary conditions, and to show maximum restraint in avoiding
any hostile action that could endanger the talks."
</P>
<P>
Ibranhim Rugova, the main Kosovo ethnic Albanian leader, named
a five-person delegation, on Friday, to re-start suspended peace
talks with Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanians, seeking independence from Belgrade and
integration into neighboring Albania, boycotted the talks in March
and they were suspended in June.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the ethnic Albanian delegation and Belgrade will
discuss all aspects of the planned settlement of the conflict,
including the region's future status.
</P>
<P>
Russia also hoped the Contact Group, acting in a coordinated
way, would continue to render Belgrade and Pristina, capital of
Kosovo, all necessary assistance in conducting the negotiation
process, the release said.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 200,000 people have been displaced from their
homes and farms in Kosovo since February when fighting began
between ethnic Albanians and Serb police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
