<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's New Tax Scheme Procures Windfall But Slows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The British government has gained
a massive windfall from the introduction of a new self-assessment
tax payment scheme, but the sharp rise in tax receipts is
considered to have contributed to the slowdown in the UK economy.
</P>
<P>
Payments in the first two months of this year alone had risen
by 7.5 billion pounds (about 12 billion U.S. dollars), a massive
rise equivalent to raising the tax rate by over 3 percent. This
has prompted allegations that the government has implemented a
"secret" tax increase.
</P>
<P>
Amid a blaze of publicity last year, the British Revenue
introduced the new self-assessment scheme which, mainly applying
to self-employed workers and those on higher incomes, was designed
to shift the onus for assessing tax from the Revenue to
individuals.
</P>
<P>
Under the new regime, late payers face strict deadlines for
payment and fines of at least 100 pounds if they are not met. The
harsh penalties for not filling in self-assessment forms have
encouraged people to pay their tax bills promptly, which has had
the effect of swelling the government's coffers.
</P>
<P>
The Inland Revenue has already fined more than three quarters
of a million people, raising 77.5 million pounds. It forecasts
issuing another 400,000 fines, according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
However, the sharp rise in tax receipts has contributed to the
slowdown in the UK economy, as higher bills are likely to have
slowed the housing market and consumer spending, according to
economists.
</P>
<P>
BBC quoted James Barty, UK economist at Deutsche Bank, as
saying, "In particular the housing market and consumer spending
have been weaker than people thought they would be. I suspect that
this hidden tax increase, as it were, has had the effect of
slowing the economy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
