<HEADLINE> Northwest China Railway Reopens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's major railway
artery, the Lanzhou-Urumqi line, was fully reopened by mid-day
after a four-hour suspension due to serious flooding.
</P>
<P>
On August 12 and 13, torrential rains destroyed four sections
of roadbed between Qiquan Lake and Shengjintai Station on the
Lanzhou-Urumqi route in eastern Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region
in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
Around 5:00 p.m. on August 13, the railway was suspended, and
passengers on three trains were stranded at several stations along
the line.
</P>
<P>
Railway workers rushed to repair the damaged roadbeds as soon
as possible, and by 9:00 p.m. on August 13, a one-way track of the
line was back in operation.
</P>
<P>
After this morning's further reinforcements, the two-way tracks
of the line were fully reopened. 
</P>
</TEXT>
