<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traffic Up for Canada's Airlines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Passenger traffic on Canada's two
major airlines increased last month because of the seasonal demand
for flights to the United States, Britain and parts of Asia.
</P>
<P>
Traffic rose 8.5 percent over the same month last year for
Canadian Airlines International Ltd., largely because of a jump in
demand for international and charter flights.
</P>
<P>
Traffic in these categories increased 12.5 percent, fueled by
flights to Britain, the United States, and especially to Hong Kong
and Taiwan where traffic rose 34 and 38 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
By comparison, the airline's domestic traffic rose only 2.1
percent from July last year, according to the Financial Post.
</P>
<P>
At Air Canada, traffic was up 6.4 percent. Business flights to
the U.S. formed the backbone of the increase, the airline said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong was also popular for Air Canada, with a 30 percent
traffic hike.
</P>
<P>
Domestic traffic by Air Canada was up only 1.2 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
Both airlines flew at almost the same capacity: 73.5 percent
for Canadian Airlines International and 73.4 percent for Air
Canada. 
</P>
