<HEADLINE> Philippine Gov't, Congress Agree to Forge Budget Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government reached
a consensus Friday night with Congress to map out a budget accord
that will spell out the government's plans and programs to be
implemented and funded for the next three years.
</P>
<P>
A news release from the Presidential Palace said the consensus
was reached after a budget accord meeting held between top
government officials and leaders of Congress.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Budget Secretary Benjamin Diokno said the
executive branch will submit to the legislature a proposed joint
House and Senate resolution calling for the formulation of the
three-year budget accord.
</P>
<P>
He said the first-ever budget accord to be forged between the
government and Congress will set ceilings on government
expenditures to ensure fiscal discipline and realize the Estrada
administration's pro-poor programs.
</P>
<P>
The government proposed the accord, which forms part of
Estrada's 10-point action agenda for the first 100 days, to guide
the administration against wasteful spending and to ensure the
delivery of public services at the least possible cost.
</P>
<P>
The three-year budget program revolves on the administration's
priority agenda of modernizing the agriculture sector, ensuring
food security, installing safety nets for sectors vulnerable to
market liberalization, creating jobs and lowering commodity
prices.
</P>
<P>
The budget plan will have to be drawn up with limited resources
and correct priorities since the new administration is grappling
with a projected 70 billion peso (1.6 billion U.S. dollar) fiscal
deficit, a 700 million peso (16.3 million dollar) domestic debt
and a 45 billion dollar foreign debt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
