<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Rebound Above 7,000 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks sharply
rebounded Friday to firm above the 7,000-point level as the
Special Administrative Region (SAR) drew on its hefty foreign
exchange reserves against speculators in the stock and futures
markets.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Hang Seng Index soared 564.27 points, or 8.47
percent Friday to end the week at 7,224.69, after diving to a new
five-year low of 6660.42 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
One hour after the stock market closed, Financial Secretary
Donald Tsang confirmed that the Hong Kong Monetary Authority
(HKMA), Hong Kong's de facto central bank, drew upon the resources
of the Exchange Fund to mount appropriate counter activities in
the stock and futures markets Friday.
</P>
<P>
The intervention brought an all-round gain in the market, with
utility, property, commerce and industry shares shooting up by
around ten percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was active at 8.547 billion HK dollars (1.096 billion
U.S. dollars), the highest over the past two months.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index advanced 2.9 percent during the week, which
saw the volatile market nose-dived to a five-year low amid fears
about the crippling Japanese yen, rumors on a possible yuan
devaluation and the break of the peg, and disappointment at poor
mid-year corporate earnings reports. 
</P>
