jumped five to seven percent in the first two hours of heavier
trading Friday, with oil stocks leading the way with gains of
13-18 percent.
</P>
<P>
President Yeltsin vowed Friday not to devalue the rouble and
appealed to parliament to hold a special mid-recess crisis session
on government draft laws in face of a financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
But a senior trader at Trinfiko, Anatoly Polun, warned that the
upward trend in share trading may not last long, and any bad news
could push prices down again.
</P>
<P>
Russian traders hoped the president's statement would help
improve the situation on the financial markets.
</P>
<P>
Though market situation is very uncertain. The market is
orientated upwards rather than downwards, Itar-Tass cited Russian
traders as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko, on a tour in the
city of Kazan, east of Moscow, on Friday, has been urging the
Duma, lower house of parliament, to pass a package of a dozen tax
and other bills, a vital part of anti-crisis austerity measures
aimed at returning economic stability.
</P>
<P>
But the Duma is yet to decide whether to hold such a session.
