<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toronto Stock Exchange Issues Internet Guidelines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Canada's largest stock exchange,
the Toronto Stock Exchange (TSE), has issued a set of proposed
guidelines for releasing stock-related information through the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines are primarily intended to provide standards for
information disseminated on the Internet and aimed at investors.
</P>
<P>
They also suggest ways for companies to respond to rumors in
chat groups or news groups.
</P>
<P>
The TSE "recommends against a company participating in a chat
or news group in order to dispel or clarify a rumor," the
guidelines say.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the company should tell the stock exchange's market
surveillance unit. If the data is false and influencing the share
price, it should consider issuing a news release.
</P>
<P>
The TSE also asks companies to "prohibit employees from
participating in Internet chat circles or news groups in talks
relating to the company or its securities."
</P>
<P>
It says all postings on company Web sites must conform to TSE
and securities regulators' disclosure rules.
</P>
<P>
The stock exchange also recommends all information given to
analysts and institutional investors be made available to all
investors via the Web, but promotional material should be
excluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0047 </DOCNO>
