<HEADLINE> Angola to Talk with IMF for Economic Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Angola government is sending
a delegation to the United States to talk with the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) over its economic reform.
</P>
<P>
Neto Costa, senior official of the Financial Ministry, who
released the news Friday, said that the delegation would talk
with IMF about a short-term loan which is due resently.
</P>
<P>
Costa did not specify the amount of the loan, but he said that
the talk may help alleviate the burden the country is
shouldering.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government, which is facing the problem of
paying back the loan, may be in a better position in talking with
the creditors if it could reach an agreement with IMF in
enhancing its economic structure reform.
</P>
<P>
The economic structure reform agreement is regarded as a
preferential policy to the low-income countries. All loans
obtained on the basis of the agreement are of low-interest (0.5%
interest rate) and long-term.
</P>
<P>
Costa said that the reform the government is to take will be
concentrated on re-structuring its expense structure and cutting
down the public expense.
</P>
<P>
It is said that about 30 percent of Angola's government budget
goes to the military, and the prolonged civil war has seriously
destroyed basic infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
IMF has been very unhappy with the financial structure in the
southern African country, so it got very little loan from IMF.
</P>
</TEXT>
