<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Video Addiction Brings Troubles for Young Canadians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- One in every four young Canadians
who play video games is addicted to them, and troubled by a
feeling of helplessness and lack of control in their lives, a
report by the Simon Fraser University (SFU) said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The study by SFU communication professor Stephen Kline surveyed
650 British Columbia youngsters and found that 25 percent reported
playing video games for seven to 30 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
The report was to be released later this month.
</P>
<P>
The rate of addiction was higher among males. Thirty percent
spent more than seven hours a week in battling figures flickering
on the computer screen.
</P>
<P>
Among females, the addiction rate was 12 percent. They play
games such as Doom, Final Fantasy and Mortal Kombat.
</P>
<P>
"I'm struck by the feelings of isolation and helplessness
expressed by the heavy players, and their desire to establish a
more balanced lifestyle," said Mr. Kline, whose research involved
questionnaires and interviews.
</P>
<P>
The SFU report warns that the global video games industry,
which amounts to a 17 billion U.S. dollars business a year, larger
than the children's television and film industry, is controlling
and shaping the play worlds of children.
</P>
<P>
"In many cases, video games are even more violent, militaristic
and graphic than anything we see on screen," Mr. Kline said, "I
don't think people are fully aware of either the scope of the
industry or the impact video games are having on our kids."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
