<HEADLINE> Campaign to Be Launched Against Child Prostitution in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Prevention was the only cure
to child prostitution in the country as it would be tough to
retrieve all victims trapped in the complex racket, Chairman of
the National Human Rights Commission Justice M. N. Venkatachaliah
said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Briefing newsmen here, he said that a campaign would be
launched by the commission on September 10 this year to combat
child prostitution.
</P>
<P>
The justice said that the complexity of the problem was such
that a more pro-active step was needed to prevent children from
falling into flesh trade.
</P>
<P>
Expressing concern over the lack of response from the society
to sexual abuse of children, he said that a massive upsurge and
condemnation by the society would put considerable pressure on
those thriving on the racket of child prostitution.
</P>
<P>
The commission would launch the campaign to sensitize law
enforcement agencies and bureaucracy through a series of programs
in collaboration with the Ministry of Social Justice and
Employment, the Delhi government, non-governmental organizations,
and Delhi police so as to build public will to combat the evil,
Venkatachaliah said. 
