<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Central Bank Announces Reform Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand (BOT), the
country's central bank, announced Friday a bank reform package,
under which the BOT orders seven financial institutions to write
down their registered and paid-up capital.
</P>
<P>
The BOT said in a press release said the seven institutions,
including two banks and five financial companies, are unable to
have sufficient recapitalization nor can they find new potential
investors within the time frame, which ends Friday.
</P>
<P>
The seven institutions, which also have high non-performing
loans, become insolvent and cannot carry on their normal
operation.
</P>
<P>
"If they are allowed to continue their operation without
rectifying the problems, losses to the public will incur," the
press release said.
</P>
<P>
The BOT thus ordered the seven institutions, namely Laem Thong
Bank, Union Bank of Bangkok, Dhana Siam Finance and Securities
Plc., First City Investment Plc., IFCT Finance and Securities
Plc., Vajiradhanathun Finance Co. Ltd., and Thai Summit Finance
and Securities Limited, to write down their registered and paid-up
capital to one satang (0.00025 U.S. dollars) per share to wipe out
losses.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, these institutions must recapitalize to meet legal
capital adequacy ratio of 8.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, with the consent of the Finance Ministry, the BOT
removed the current Boards of Directors of these institutions and
appointed new Board of Directors, which have started working from
Friday.
</P>
<P>
After the BOT's intervention and appointment of the new
management, these two banks and 12 finance companies, including
the seven companies taken over by the BOT earlier in May, shall be
restructured.
</P>
<P>
Laem Thong Bank will be merged with Radhanasin Bank, a bank the
government set up in March this year to take care of the assets of
the ill financial companies, and find foreign strategic partners
later.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Union Bank of Bangkok will be merged with
Krungthai Thanakit, a financial company under the state-owned
commercial Krungthai Bank, and the 12 finance companies after
which foreign investors or strategic partners will be arranged
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
The package has gained the approval of a special Cabinet
meeting later Friday.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement between the Thai government and the
International Monetary Fund, commercial banks in Thailand must
recapitalize before the deadline of August 14.
</P>
<P>
But only four of the 15 banks have been able to raise capital
or find new foreign strategic partners. The banks have either
suspended new loans or cut credit lines as they have been unable
to raise capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Philippine Soldiers Killed in Ambush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Three members of the Philippines'
Armed Forces Geographical Unit were killed and three others were
wounded in an ambush Friday morning in the southern province of
Basilan.
</P>
<P>
Initial police reports indicated that the ambush took place
while the victims were on their way to the town of Lamitan for an
important meeting, according to the Philippine News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The unit commander and two unit members died on the spot from
multiple gunshot wounds when an undetermined number of
heavily-armed men attacked them.
</P>
<P>
The unit was not able to fight back as the ambushers caught
them by surprise while they were on board a jeep.
</P>
<P>
Police authorities who rushed to the crime scene were not able
to catch up with the perpetrators who immediately fled after the
ambush.
</P>
<P>
Police said the motive could be about a dispute on the land
that the unit was tasked to supervise by a businessman. But they
have yet to establish the real motive behind the broad daylight
killing.
</P>
<P>
The local police are still pursuing the unidentified suspects.
</P>
</TEXT>
