<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Manufacturers Expect Dwindling Orders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong manufacturers
anticipate a drop in volume of orders in the second half of 1998
compared with the same period of 1997, a government survey showed
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers engaged in fabricated metal, printing, textiles,
electronic and electrical, and electrical machinery industry
generally expect a fall in volume of orders in the latter half of
1998, according to the Business Prospects Survey, conducted
recently by the Census and Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
Construction firms also predict a fall in volume of orders, but
apparel manufacturers anticipate a fairly stable number.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that manufacturers predict stable capacity
utilization, lower profit margins, and shrinking exports in the
second half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted on a half-yearly basis, covers about 300
firms from major manufacturing industries, the import and export
trade, the banking industry and the construction sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
