<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Super Hybrid Rice to Be Born in China By 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- A super high-yielding hybrid
rice whose per-hectare output may be 20 percent higher than the
present hybrids will be born in China by 2000, a reknowned hybrid
rice expert announced here today.
</P>
<P>
As a result of breakthroughs in breeding technology, the super
rice can produce 12,000 kilograms per hectare after a growth
period of 120 days, said Yuan Longping, director of the China
National Hybrid Rice Research and Development Center.
</P>
<P>
The daily yield per unit area is designed to be 100 kilos per
hectare, so even higher outputs can be achieved after a longer
growth period, Yuan told the ongoing 18th International Congress
of Genetics.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural scientist believes that the new hybrid will be
of great significance to China's grain supply in the coming
decades as the country's population continues to grow.
</P>
<P>
Seeding the rice on 6.6 million hectares of paddy fields in
2003 is expected to add 15 million tons of rice to the nation's
store, or eight percent of the annual grain yield, according to
Yuan.
</P>
<P>
His center launched the super rice program initiated by the
Ministry of Agriculture in 1996, aimed at achieving a yield of
9,750 kilos per hectare in the succeeding two years.
</P>
<P>
However, trial planting in small plots of land has yielded more
than 13,000 kilos per hectare, and large-scale experiments will be
started in Hunan and Sichuan provinces next year, Yuan said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no question that we can fulfill the goal or even be
more successful by 2000," he told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
China is not the only country to implement the super rice
program, but may be the first one to complete the effort.
</P>
<P>
The first breeding program for super high-yielding rice was
initiated in Japan in 1980 with the aim of developing new
varieties capable of outyielding the old ones by 50 percent within
15 years.
</P>
<P>
"But it hasn't been reported successful so far," Yuan said.
</P>
<P>
The International Rice Research Institute also started the
super rice program to develop 12,000 kilos of rice per hectare
within 120 days, the same as Yuan's. But the goal will not be
fulfilled until 2005, said Yuan, who is the chief consultant of
the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The 68-year-old academician with the Chinese Academy of
Engineering has helped China increase its grain output by over 300
million tons since he bred the world's first hybrid rice in 1973.
</P>
<P>
These hybrids now have been introduced into some 20 countries
and regions around the world 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
