<HEADLINE> Lesotho Army, Opposition Leaders Meet After Chaos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Commanders of the Lesotho
army, the police and leaders of opposition parties were meeting
in capital Maseru Friday following Thursday's violent clashes
between government's supporters and opponents.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held at the Catholic archbishop's residence,
South African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The topics of the meeting is not yet known, the report said.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted a source in the royal palace as saying that they
only became aware of the meeting when the involved parties were
looking for a venue.
</P>
<P>
"We offered them the royal palace but it was not acceptable to
others... We do not know what is being discussed. There is no
minister, prime minister or (King) Letsie's representative in the
meeting," the source said.
</P>
<P>
Pro- and anti-government factions clashed Thursday in Maseru
in which nine people were injured and two shops were looted and
set alight.
</P>
<P>
Opposition party supporters have been protesting outside the
royal palace since last Tuesday against the result of the May
general election.
</P>
<P>
They claim the election was rigged in favor of the ruling
Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD) and are demanding fresh
polls.
</P>
<P>
The LCD won 79 of 80 seats in the National Assembly. 
