<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi Arabia's Stock Market continued to fall in both
trading volume and value for the second week in a row, the Arabic
daily Al Hayat reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The number of shares that changed hands last week decreased to
2.93 million from 6.06 million in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
The turnover fell to 115 million U.S. dollars from 219 million
dollars the week before, a fall of 47.7 percent. Moreover, the
number of transactions dropped to 3,929 from 5880 in the previous
week, a drop of 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's trade deficit with Asia, including
central Asia and the Far East, has grown to 21 million dollars
this year, compared with a trade surplus of 800 million dollars in
the first seven months of 1997, the English daily The Jerusalem
Post reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel's trade surplus with the U.S. nearly doubled
to 1.6 billion dollars in the period, while the huge deficit with
the European Union shrank by 23 percent to 3.6 billion dollars
from 4.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Israel's total trade deficit for the first seven months stood
at 3.47 billion dollars, a 26 percent drop from 4.67 billion
dollars in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The number of jobless people who registered with
Israel's Employment Service dropped by 3.4 percent in July from
164,200 in June to 158,600, the Haaretz newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The service said in a statement that the statistics of the
last four months suggested the trend in rising unemployment had
been stopped.
</P>
<P>
But analysts said the figure did not reflect the real picture
of the unemployment. According to Israel's Central Bureau of
Statistics, the number of the jobless was 210,000 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
