<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Publicity Blitz Launched in Australia to Sell Tax Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Australian government has
begun its pre-election publicity blitz to sell its newly-released
tax reform plans.
</P>
<P>
The publicity blitz began Friday as Australian Prime Minister
John Howard appeared in at least seven domestic radio or
television programs Friday advocating the tax reform package
unveiled Thursday, and will be followed by a series of national
print and television advertisements beginning this weekend.
</P>
<P>
Tax reform package coverage dominated Friday's edition of
Australia's national newspapers, and radio and television news
programs.
</P>
<P>
The package, which was designed to reform the nation's 70
year-old tax system, appeared acceptable to the majority of the
Australians as they are set to benefit from the government's
proposed tax cuts and compensation packages, including income tax
cuts for middle- and low-income earners.
</P>
<P>
In a speech Friday afternoon in Adelaide, capital city of South
Australian state, Howard said under his plan, up to 80 percent of
the workforce would pay a maximum 30 cents in the dollar tax, with
most unlikely to ever move up into a higher tax bracket.
</P>
<P>
That means middle- and low- income earners would pay less
income tax for the same amount of income after the introduction of
the proposed income tax.
</P>
<P>
Howard said the reform package would provide an incentive for
workers to take on a second job or work overtime.
</P>
<P>
"This is very much a taxation reform for middle Australia," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We've devised tax scales for families, for middle
Australia..." he added.
</P>
<P>
Organizations representing the nation's farmers, small
business, and some leading banks have already announced their
support for the reform plans, which would bring cost reduction to
them through tax cuts or scrapping of some existing taxes.
</P>
<P>
The national print and television advertisement campaign, which
will begin this weekend, would cost 6 million U.S. dollars,
Special Minister of State Nick Minchin said in a statement Friday.
</P>
<P>
Tax reform information hotlines have already been set up by the
government to help the public understand the reform plans.
</P>
<P>
Detailed information about the reform plans is also available
on a government's website on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
It is believed the prime minister would call a federal
election in October, leaving about one month for the government,
whose first term expires in March, 1999, to persuade the voters to
accept its tax reform plans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
