<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Chinese Navy Commander's Final Resting Place Is The Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Deng Zhaoxiang, a former deputy
commander of the Chinese Navy who died on August 6 at the age of
95, was cremated in Beijing today and will return to the place he
loved and belonged to when his ashes are released into the sea.
</P>
<P>
Deng spent much of his life in the navy, and for 72 years
watched it grow in strength and participated in some colorful
events, one of which made him famous across China, when he led the
officers and enlisted men of the Kuomintang warship "Chongqing" in
revolt and went over to the People's Liberation Army in early 1949.
</P>
<P>
Deng was born in 1903 in Gaoyao, Guangdong Province, and
entered Whampoa Navy Academy in 1914 at the age of 11. After
graduation, he attended the Yantai Naval Academy, and Nanjing
Torpedo and Gun Academy. In 1928, he was sent to Britain by the
KMT Government to study at the Greenwich Royal Navy Academy and
Navy Torpedo School.
</P>
<P>
He returned to China on the eve of the War of Resistance to
Japan (1937-1945) and served as head of training and education at
the Tongzi Naval Academy in 1942. After World War II, he served as
captain of the cruiser "Chongqing" and later organized the revolt.
</P>
<P>
After 1949, Deng was appointed successively president of the
Andong Naval Academy and the Naval Mosquito Boat Academy,
vice-president of the First Naval Academy, and a naval base deputy
chief of staff and deputy commander. Moreover, he served as deputy
fleet commander of the PLA naval forces and deputy commander of
the Chinese navy from 1960 to 1981 and contributed tremendously to
improving PLA naval forces.
</P>
<P>
After 1983, he became vice-chairman of the national committee
of the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC)
until 1998 and took an active part in social and political
activities, committing himself to fact-finding tours to factories,
rural areas, army units, schools, and construction sites.
</P>
<P>
He concerned himself very much with the reunification of the
motherland and worked towards that goal in his later years.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0079 </DOCNO>
