<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK People Make Donations To Help Mainland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Helpful Hong Kong residents
from all walks of life have been making donations through
different channels in the past several weeks to help their
flood-stricken compatriots on the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
The Special Administrative Region (SAR) government has
contributed 9 million HK dollars (1.2 million U.S. dollars)
through three local relief organizations.
</P>
<P>
On top of government aid, local dignitaries and ordinary people
have demonstrated their generosity at times of economic adversity.
 They are actively making donations either in cash or in relief
materials to ease the pains suffered by the flood victims along a
swollen Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The major charity organization Hong Kong Red Cross said Monday
it was approaching its target of 10 million HK dollars (1.3
million U.S. dollars) after about a week's fund-raising
activities. Of that, 3 million HK dollars (385,000 U.S. dollars)
was a grant from the SAR government's disaster relief fund.
</P>
<P>
The local Red Cross will be sending delegates to the flooded
provinces to monitor and help with the relief program.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Red Cross, World Vision Hong Kong, Oxfam Hong
Kong and Medecins Sans Frontieres have in the past days published
their accounts on major newspapers into which people can directly
transfer donations.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Alliance for the Betterment of Hong Kong raised
more than one million HK dollars for the victims through various
fund-raising activities and handed the sum to the local Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the party Tsang Yok-sing praised the people of Hong
Kong for their generosity in the midst of the economic slump.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua News Agency Hong Kong Branch said that up to Wednesday,
Hong Kong people had donated around 66 million HK dollars (8.5
million U.S. dollars), of which businessman Li Ka-shing
contributed 50 million HK dollars (6.4 million U.S. dollars), to
the flood victims through the agency.
</P>
<P>
Around one hundred vendors in Yau Ma Tei, Kowloon, held a
one-day charity sale on Thursday to raise funds for the victims,
which drew warm responses from neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
A fruit vendor told reporters that, being Chinese, Hong Kong
people can not stand on the sidelines while their compatriots were
suffering from the severe flooding. He said wholesalers had
distributed fruits to them at lowest prices.
</P>
<P>
Concerned about the mainland floods, the Hong Kong garrison of
the People's Liberation Army have raised more than one million HK
dollars (128,000 U.S. dollars) to help the victims.
</P>
<P>
About 10,000 soldiers participated in fund-raising activities
Wednesday at military barracks across Hong Kong and at their
Shenzhen base, according to a spokesman for the garrison.
</P>
<P>
Since July, local media have been giving wide coverage of the
worst flooding in nearly half a century in China.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa last week appealed for Hong Kong
people to help the victims. "I understand very well that Hong Kong
is experiencing an economic downturn and many citizens feel very
frustrated in the face of economic or unemployment problems," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"But I would like to point out that the victims on the mainland
are now facing a very serious disaster," Tung told his fellow
people, asking everyone to lend a hand "to help our compatriots
out."
</P>
<P>
The latest of the fund-raising events will be two gala shows
this weekend which will be broadcast live.
</P>
<P>
Asia Television Ltd. (ATV) and Wharf Cable Television Ltd. will
jointly produce a show Friday night while Television Broadcasts
Ltd. (TVB) will organize a seven-hour event together with major
charities on Saturday night. Hotlines are to be set up during the
two shows for donations.
</P>
<P>
At the request of the SAR government, six major charity
organizations in Hong Kong -- the Yan Chai Hospital, the Pok Oi
Hospital, the Tung Wah Group of Hospitals, the Po Leung Kuk, the
Yan Oi Tong and the Lok Sin Tong Benevolent Society -- announced
Thursday they will get together to raise funds for the victims in
coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
"It is, as I can recall, the first time for such large-scale
collaboration," said Director of Home Affairs Shelley Lau.
</P>
<P>
The highlight of their joint efforts will be a flag day,
planned for late next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
