<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China Paradise for White Stork </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 14 (Xinhua)-- The Honghe Marshland Nature
Reserve, located some 300 km from Jiamusi City in northeast
China's Heilongjiang Province, is one of China's largest natural
habitats for stork.
</P>
<P>
China is home to some 1,000 white stork, a rare water bird
species on the brink of extinction, with approximately one-fifth
the species living in the Honghe Reserve. Now white storks thrive
on small fish and shrimp in the reserve.
</P>
<P>
The reserve is also home to over 160 species of birds, 25
animals and 1,000 plant species. Twenty-odd rare species in the
reserve are under state protection, including the white storks,
red-crested crane, lynx, leopards and swans.
</P>
<P>
The reserve, established in 1984, covers 20,000
hectares. Ecologists agree that the reserve is the sole surviving
primitive marsh ecosystem in China.
</P>
<P>
Swamps cover over half of the reserve, with grassy marshlands
account for 40 percent and forests 10 percent of the total land
area.
</P>
<P>
Visitors to the reserve can catch a glimpse of three species of
rabbit and watch red deer feeding on the abundant grass. The
thickly wild flora and flowers in the reserve are frequented by
flocks of birds and forest frogs.
</P>
<P>
The skies above the forest most often features flocks of white
storks and Mandarin can be seen swimming in weeds characteristic
of the marshes.
</P>
<P>
Reserve Manager Zhu Baoguang points out that local government
efforts have protected the primitive ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
"Abandoned telephone poles and wires represent the only
evidence of human activity in the grassy marshland," according to
the official.
</P>
<P>
The local government has invested millions of yuan to protect
the reserve, said Zhu, adding that 10 workers currently maintain
the area.
</P>
<P>
Zhu pointed out that the employees of three neighboring farms
are prohibited from encroaching on the resevere, and all
individuals causing damage are subject to severe punishment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Sends Airbus to Evacuate Expatriates from D.R. Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 14 (Xinhua) -- France Friday sent an Airbus
passenger plane to the Democratic Republic of Congo (D.R. Congo)
to evacuate the French expatriates who wish to leave the country.
</P>
<P>
"A civilian Airbus was sent this morning to the Democratic
Republic of Congo for facilitate the departure of the people who
wish to," said French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne
Gazeau-Secret.
</P>
<P>
About 100 out of the 500 French nationals remaining in the D.R.
Congo have expressed wish to leave the country.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all the international commercial flights to Kinshasa have
been suspended because of the risky situation in the D.R. Congo.
</P>
<P>
If the Airbus cannot land in Kinshasa, it will land in another
nearby city such as Libreville of Gabon, said the spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is changing very quickly and we are following
its evolution with much vigilance," she said.
</P>
<P>
Fighting was reported around the Inga hydro-electricity dam
near Boma, 400 kilometers southwest of Kinshasa, between the
rebellious Banyamulenge forces and government forces loyal to
President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Kinshasa has been deprived of both water and electricity since
Thursday, because of the fighting around Inga power station.
</P>
<P>
The Inga power center was the supplier of electricity for
Kinshasa, the province of Bas-Congo in the southwest, Katanga in
the southeast, and the capital of the Congo Republic Brazzaville
on the other side of the Congo River. 
</P>
