<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donations for Flood Victims Arrive Daily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Civil Affairs
today received donations of some 10 million yuan to provide relief
for flood victims in southern China, raising total donations over
the past four days to 110 million yuan (13.29 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Today's donations included 7.92 million yuan in cash and relief
materials valued at 1.3 million yuan, according to an unnamed
Ministry official.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry opened a hotline and two special accounts on
Monday to handle both domestic and foreign donations.
</P>
<P>
The heaviest rainstorms in decades have pelted a dozen
provinces and regions in southern China since the beginning of
summer causing serious flooding and leaving enormous losses in
their wake.
</P>
<P>
Since early July, the Yangtze River Basin has witnessed the
heaviest flooding since 1954, with provinces in the middle and
lower reaches of the Yangtze, including Hubei, Hunan and Jiangxi
provinces, engaged in all-out efforts to prevent and stop breaches
in major dams along the river.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Civil Affairs has placed the death toll at more
than 2,000 people, and released statistics showing that floods
have adversely affected more than 200 million people.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry has distributed donated relief materials such as
clothing, medical supplies, bottled water, disinfectants, tents
and cement, to heavily flooded areas in a number of provinces,
including Jiangxi, Hunan, Hubei and Anhui.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the State Postal Service Bureau distributed separate
circulars to post offices across China on Wednesday and Friday
instructing related facilities to provide free postal services for
people sending donations to the Civil Affairs Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The Disaster Relief Department under the Ministry of Civil
Affairs will handle all donations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
