<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Deplores Recruitment of Child Soldiers in DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) has deplored the latest recruitment into armed
service of hundreds of children, some as young as 12, in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
"We are particularly concerned about the re-enlistment of
400-500 former child soldiers from a transit center near Kisangani
and more than 100 children in Bukavu who had been demobilized and
prepared for reintegration into families," the UNICEF said in a
statement issued here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The UNICEF also said that the present hostilities in the DRC
have put on hold vital UNICEF programs including a scheduled
nationwide polio vaccination campaign and work to help the
children rejoin their families.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. agency called for an immediate ceasefire to make it
possible for the polio vaccination campaign to proceed as planned
and for children to return to school. The DRC has the highest
incidence of polio in the world.
</P>
<P>
In the same statement, the UNICEF said it is also gravely
concerned about the fate of children and women who have reportedly
been abducted during the current conflict in the African country.
</P>
<P>
It appealed to both sides of the conflict to renounce detention
of ethnic adversaries and to release all those who have been
detained to date. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
