<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Trade Deficit Declines Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' trade deficit
fell 73.8 percent to 1.47 billion U.S. dollars during the first
half of 1998 from 5.6 billion dollars recorded a year earlier, the
National Statistics Office said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The country's merchandise exports reached 13.9 billion dollars
during the first half of the year, 18.8 percent higher than the
same period last year, according to figures released by the
office.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, imports dropped to 15.4 billion dollars during the
period, 11.3 percent lower than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
For June 1998, the country registered a monthly surplus of 130
million dollars, with exports and imports amounting to 2.39
billion dollars and 2.12 billion dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
The United States was the country's largest trading partner
during the period, with their total trade volume reaching 3.5
billion dollars. Japan and South Korea followed with a total trade
volume of 3.1 billion dollars and 1.1 billion dollars
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
