<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Draws on Foreign Reserves Against Speculators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) Friday drew on its hefty foreign
exchange reserves to counterattack speculators in the stock and
futures markets, a top financial official confirmed.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Hang Seng Index sharply rebounded 564.27 points,
or 8.47 percent to close at 7,224.69 Friday, after diving to a new
five-year low of 6660.42 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
SAR Financial Secretary Donald Tsang told a promptly-called
press conference Friday: "I have exercised my power under the
Exchange Fund Ordinance and asked the Hong Kong Monetary Authority
(HKMA) to draw upon the resources of the Exchange Fund to mount
appropriate counter activities in the stock and futures markets."
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that the HKMA, Hong Kong's de facto central bank,
mounted counter activities earlier Friday.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong held 96.5 billion US dollars worth of foreign
exchange reserves as at the end of June 1998, ranking the third in
the world after Japan and the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
"I must make clear that we are not against the shorting of Hang
Seng Index futures by hedge funds, or indeed by anybody," said
Tsang." "But we do not tolerate attempts by speculators to
manipulate our interest rates by engineering extreme conditions in
the money market so that they can benefit from the short positions
they have built up in Hang Seng Index futures."
</P>
<P>
The Financial Secretary reiterated that Kong Kong's
long-standing policy of non-intervention in the stock and futures
markets remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
"No intervention may take place unless a sufficiently clear
linkage exists between the currency play and the stock and futures
market play," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tsang also reaffirmed the government's resolve in maintaining
the linked exchange rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
