<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Kill 625 People in Hunan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- This year's floods have claimed
the lives of 625 people in central China's Hunan Province and have
left more than a million homeless, according to a provincial flood
control and drought relief headquarters source.
</P>
<P>
Since mid-June, water from the Xiangjiang River and Dongting
Lake has flooded 7 prefectures and cities and 19 counties and
destroyed more than 1 million houses, affecting the lives of
several million people. A million people have been evacuated to
safer places.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of soldiers and civilians today are
fortifying the banks of Dongting Lake to prevent more damage from
the fifth flood crest on the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
In the southern part of the province, people are battling a
severe lingering drought that has affected 470,000 people and
400,000 ha. of farmland in 52 counties and 800 towns.
</P>
<P>
In Zhuzhou, one of the worst drought-hit cities, there has been
no precipitation for the past 40 days.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists here say the province's disasters in the middle
reaches of the Yangtze are related to the El Nino phenomenon, and
warn that it may bring a plague of insects with it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
