<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dike Breach Near China's Largest Oilfield </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAQING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- A breach in a 500-m. dike of the
Nenjiang River in the city of Daqing in northeast China's
Heilongjiang Province at 6 a.m. today is threatening the Daqing
Oilfield, China's largest oil producer.
</P>
<P>
Recent reports show that the attempt to shore up the collapsed
embankment 100 km from downtown Daqing has been given up owing to
a lack of laborers.
</P>
<P>
Some 20,000 residents have been evacuated but life is normal
and there is no price-hikes in the city.
</P>
<P>
The floods have forced the oilfield to close down 155 wells,
but most of its nearly 20,000 wells are still operating
normally. In 1997, Daqing's oil output was 60.9 million tons, half
the country's total.
</P>
<P>
Some 170,000 local people, soldiers, and police are busy
reinforcing two secondary dikes and the Heiyupao Reservoir to
protect the wells, power plants, water plants, and urban area.
</P>
<P>
The dikes have been reinforced with 11,38 million sandbags and
282.3 km of secondary dikes have also been reinforced.
</P>
<P>
The State Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters and the
provincial government are allocating 2 million sandbags and other
materials and large quantities of relief goods for Daqing.
</P>
<P>
Daqing Oilfield began operation in the early 1960s. The city
itself was established on December 4, 1979 on 21,000 sq.km. of
land. It has a population of 2.34 million.
</P>
<P>
In 1969, a flood that hit the oilfield caused a number of
deaths, but oil production did not stop because of strenuous
efforts by local people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
