<HEADLINE> Hunan Vegetable Prices Back to Normal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Price hikes are under control
and vegetable supplies have returned to normal in most
flood-stricken areas in central China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
Heavy flooding since June have affected over 108 Hunan cities
and counties, and by the end of July had inundated over 54,666
hectares of vegetable production bases, sparking price hikes of
between 50-100 percent in some cities.
</P>
<P>
Local governments addressed the problem by allocating special
funds and establishing preferential prices for seeds, fertilizer,
and pesticide, as well as recommending new varieties with short
maturation periods.
</P>
<P>
Vegetable traders from neighboring provinces have also been
encouraged to offer products in Hunan. 
</P>
