<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployment in S. Africa Rising: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Unemployment in South
Africa has been on the rise, increasing from 21 percent in 1996
to 22.9 percent in 1997, according to a survey released by the
Central Statistical Service (CSS).
</P>
<P>
For 1995 and 1994 the figure were 16.9 percent and 20 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
This is according to a new definition of unemployment adopted
by the CSS. Based on the previous definition, now called the
expanded unemployment rate, unemployment rose from 29.2 percent
through 35.6 percent to 37.6 percent between 1995 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
The CSS's new definition of unemployment was in line with the
International Labor Organization definition, CSS chief Mark Orkin
said.
</P>
<P>
The definition was preferred by more than 80 percent of both
developed and less developed countries, and by South Africa's
major trading partners, he said.
</P>
<P>
The CSS's previous definition provided for two criteria for
respondents to the surveys to be classified as unemployed.
Firstly, they had not worked during the last seven days before
being questioned. Secondly, they want to work and are available
to start working within a week.
</P>
<P>
The new definition adds a third requirement, that they had
taken active steps to look for work or to start some form of
self-employment in the four weeks prior to the interview.
</P>
<P>
Based on the preliminary census results, there were an
estimated 22.3 million people in South Africa in 1997 aged
between 15 and 65 years, considered to be the working population.
</P>
<P>
About 7.5 million (32.6 percent) of them were gainfully
employed. The highest unemployment rate, 29.3 percent was among
blacks, while 16 percent of coloreds, 10.2 percent of Indians and
4.6 of whites were unemployed.
</P>
<P>
The largest share of the employed (36.1 percent) fell into the
community, social and personal services sector, followed by
manufacturing (17.7 percent) and the wholesale, retail and
accommodation sector (16.3 percent).
</P>
<P>
"The impact of unemployment is being increasingly experienced
by women, Orkin said.
</P>
<P>
Based on the CSS's new definition of employment, 34.6 percent
of black women were unemployed in 1997 compared to 24.6 percent
of men. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Firms Conduct Business Via Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Zhao Lunjie, who joined the
Internet just six month ago, today enjoys a flood of business
inquiries and orders from scores of foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
"A short six months ago we were an unknown entity and seldom
received orders," according to Zhao, general manager of the
Shanghai Lansheng Golf Equipment Co. Ltd. "The Internet has
enabled us to access the international market."
</P>
<P>
Over half of China's 15,000 medium- to large-sized state-owned
enterprises are conducting business via the Internet and a growing
number of small firms are following suit, according to the State
Economic and Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
Experts noted that Internest use by enterprises represents the
third trend in the arrival of the Information Age in China,
followed by the popularization of personal computers and
establishment of information industry programs funded by the
government.
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade firms, the most enthusiastic users of the
Internet during the first six months of this year established
numerous websites, more than 1,000 export firms attempted to
promote sales using the website offered by the Asian Resources, a
Philippine-based trade intermediary.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation set up
the China Market, a special website providing information on
products, on July 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
"Accessing the Internet has greatly improved the international
competitiveness of Chinese firms," according to Sarah Benecke,
president of Asian Resources.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts have pointed out that China's fledgling
electronic information industry offers vast potential for
development. Moreover, they suggest the adoption of relevant laws
and regulations covering security and fees, forms of taxation and
the reduction of risks to the maximum, as well as the prevention
of price wars and global problems currently confronting the
industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
