<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 08:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey's Opposition Denies Forming Election Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's leading opposition
Virtue Party (FP) has denied the accusation that the opposition
parties attempted to form an alliance for the early elections next
year, the Daily News newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
FP's Deputy Chairman Ismail Alptekin at a press conference here
Thursday brushed aside claims by the ruling coalition that the
opposition was trying to form such an alliance. He clarified that
the recent talks among the five opposition parties were only aimed
at seeking a dialog instead of an election alliance.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of five opposition parties, including the FP, True Path
Party (DYP), Democratic Party, Liberal Democratic Party and
Rebirth Party, held a meeting in Istanbul late Tuesday, which drew
severe criticism from the ruling coalition parties.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's meeting was held because "there must be a sound
dialog established in order to solve the country's problems,"
said Alptekin.
</P>
<P>
He accused the coalition parties, namely Motherland Party,
Democratic Left Party and Democratic Turkey Party, of trying to
find ways to evade the early elections.
</P>
<P>
"No one can escape from the elections. It must be held at the
time agreed by the parliament," Alptekin said.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Parliament has decided that the early elections
will be held in April 1999.
</P>
<P>
The closer cooperation between the pro-Islamic FP, a successor
of the former Welfare Party closed by the court, and the DYP has
triggered harsh reaction from the ruling coalition which reminded
the people not to forget the past of the two parties.
</P>
<P>
The former FP-DYP coalition government led by Necmettin
Erbakan was forced to step down in June 1997 by the powerful
military for its alleged attempt to undermine the country's
secular systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
