<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Investing Heavily on Rural Power Grids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 14 (Xinhua) -- China plans to spend 100 billion
yuan on the upgrading of its rural power grids in some 2,000
counties from now to 2000.
</P>
<P>
Economists say the move would enable more rural households to
use electrical appliances.
</P>
<P>
The project will start on a trial basis in 500 better off
counties this year.
</P>
<P>
Electricity is still limited in many rural parts of China and
washing machines and refrigerators often sit unused at home for
much of the year.
</P>
<P>
Studies found that there were only 8 refrigerators, 27 color
TV sets and 22 washing machines for every 100 rural households in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Take Shanxi Province in north China for instance. The power
supply in its rural areas is far from meeting the growing
demand. Rural households consume only a dozen kwh of electricity
on average per month.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi will raise 10 billion yuan over the next three years to
improve its power grids in rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
