<HEADLINE> Flood Crest Passes Chinese City Of Qiqihar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 14 (Xinhua) -- A flood crest on the Nenjiang
River in northeastern China passed through Qiqihar, a major
industrial center in Heilongjiang Province, at 2:00 a.m. today,
pushing the water level there to 146.05 m., 0.39 m. above the
record.
</P>
<P>
The water on the main stream of the Songhua River in Harbin,
Heilongjiang's provincial capital, rose to 119.17 m., 0.11
m. higher than yesterday's level and 1.07 m. above the danger
mark, and it's still rising.
</P>
<P>
The water level at the Dalai measuring point in neighboring
Jilin Province was 131 m. today, 1.02 m. higher than the record.
</P>
<P>
Weather forecasts call for rain on the western part of the
Liaohe River around August 18, bringing a third flood crest on the
river.
</P>
<P>
The floods will endanger six hydroelectric power stations along
the river because of their inability to control floods.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the water in the Dongting and Poyang lakes receded
slowly today. The water level at Shashi in central China's Hubei
Province was 44.6 m. at 12 hours today, 0.24 m. lower than during
the flood crest. The level at the city of Jiujiang in east China's
Jiangxi Province dropped by 0.04 m. from Thursday to 22.61
m. today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
