<HEADLINE> Shenzhen's Renminbi Business At Overseas Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Shenzhen, a special economic
zone in southern China's Guangdong Province, became China's second
city with foreign financial institutions doing renminbi business
after obtaining People's Bank of China approval.
</P>
<P>
The Shenzhen Branch of the People's Bank of China said today
that only foreign financial institutions that have operated in
China for 3 fiscal years and have made a profit for 2 consecutive
years can trade in renminbi.
</P>
<P>
They should have on average at least 150 million US dollars in
outstanding loans monthly, a year prior to making application, and
that of Sino-overseas joint venture and solely-foreign-owned banks
and financial companies should be 100 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
In a 22-article document the bank spelled out rules on
inter-bank call activities, the assets to liability ratio, and
applications for short-term renminbi financing.
</P>
<P>
There are 25 foreign financial institutions in Shenzhen. They
are major providers of foreign currency loans for local
enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
