<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fewer Births and Deaths in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand saw fewer births
and deaths in the year ending in June than the previous
corresponding period, a government release said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Births registered in the year to June totalled 56,559, a drop
of 751 or 1.3 per cent from the previous period. Meanwhile, the
fertility rate fell fractionally from 1.96 to 1.94 births per
woman.
</P>
<P>
The fertility rate per woman "is now 8 percent below the level
required by the population to replace itself without migration,"
the release said.
</P>
<P>
The trend away from early childbearing is continuing, it said,
adding that the average age of women having children in the year
was 28.9 years, compared with 28.7 years in the previous year and
27.8 years in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Deaths registered in the year ending in June totalled 27,132,
down 673 or 2.4 per cent from a year earlier. As births fell by a
greater margin than deaths, the gap between births and deaths, or
the natural increase of the population, narrowed slightly from
29,505 in the year ending in June 1997 to 29,427 in the following
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
