<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plummet in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices tumbled in Tokyo on
Friday on fears of a global economic crisis, but buybacks prevented
the key Nikkei 225 index from falling below 15,000.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange closed at 15,123.93, down 258.09
points, or 1.68 percent, from Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, fell 12.91 points or 1.09 percent to 1,168.80.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section increased to an estimated 430 million
shares from Thursday's 333.27 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Another drop in New York shares overnight sparked large selling
orders of export-heavy blue chips in the Tokyo market in the morning.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei slid dangerously close to 15,000, notching the day's low
of 15,049.45, but recovered some ground as investors hunted for
bargains.
</P>
<P>
A strong rebound in the Hong Kong and Singapore stock markets in
the afternoon appeared to be a supporting factor for Tokyo shares,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,335 issues listed on the First Section, losers outpaced
gainers 766 to 335, with 170 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
