<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiangsu Manufacturers Handle Exports Internally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- An increasing number of Chinese
manufacturers which previously relied on export services provided
by state foreign trade companies are responding to government
encouragement and handling exports themselves.
</P>
<P>
State-owned and collective manufacturing enterprises in east
China's Jiangsu Province, the nation's second largest exporter,
currently handle close to 10 percent of local exports.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC)
had granted approval for 1,265 state-owned and collective
manufacturers in Jiangsu to undertake foreign trade activities by
the end of June this year. Related enterprises account for close
to 14 percent of the total number of firms in the province.
</P>
<P>
The companies have increased their contribution to the
province's exports from 3.1 percent to 10.5 percent over the past
five years alone, with direct exports for the first half of this
year growing by 11.5 percent on the 1997 period to 775 million US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Local officials attribute the increase to efforts local
enterprises have made to explore both domestic and international
markets.
</P>
<P>
The change has also helped manufacturers improve internal
management and adopt advanced international product
standards. Many of the manufacturers have also established foreign
subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
For example, the Nanjing Jincheng Group Co. Ltd., a major
motorcycle producer with dozens of proprietary stores in a number
of foreign countries, including Colombia, Cambodia, Bangladesh and
Poland, arranges production schedules according to demand. The
company has in turn doubled annual exports for two successive
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Putting An End To Supply Shortages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey of 601 major
commodities on the Chinese market showed a balance of supply and
demand and even an oversupply in some cases for the first half of
the year.
</P>
<P>
The long periods of shortages that hampered China's economic
growth have come to an end, according to Chen Huai, a research
fellow at the State Council Development Research Center.
</P>
<P>
A study by the China Internal Trade Bureau's Information Center
of the 1985-89 period showed supply far short of demand. Supply
and demand were balanced from the latter half of 1996 to the first
half of 1997, and since then it has been a buyer's market, one of
the welcome results of the change from a planned economy to a
market-driven one.
</P>
<P>
The change has also resulted in greater competition in product
quality and after-sales service, with ordinary consumers
benefitting from the wider range of choice. In fact, many young
Chinese nowadays hardly know what long queues or rationed
commodities are.
</P>
<P>
China has greater demand for large-scale investment in various
sectors and has used imported technology and managerial techniques
to improve quality.
</P>
<P>
Economists agree that there is still weak demand in China at
present, but consumer demand is growing.
</P>
<P>
The Research Center's Chen said that, although an oversupply
could lead to a reduction of industrial profits and a slack
market, it cannot be regarded as a step backward, but suggests
rather that China has reached the primary stage of industrial
development and that obstacles in the sphere of production have
been removed.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Chinese government has taken a series of measures
to help stop oversupplies with interest cuts, providing mortgages,
and infrastructure investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
