<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Beach Resort Promotes Environmental 'Green Card' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANYA, August 14 (Xinhua)-- Tourists to the beach-side resort
of Sanya on the island province of Hainan will receive a "green
card" from their hotel.
</P>
<P>
It is not a "green card" in its original sense, but a reminder
for environmental protection. In three languages -- Chinese,
English and Japanese -- the document asks guests to help save
water and washing powder by putting unused towels on the rack, for
example.
</P>
<P>
Located at the southernmost tip of Hainan, Sanya is one of the
most popular tourist destinations in China, renowned for its clear
blue sea and white beaches. In the first half of this year,
780,000 Chinese and overseas tourists visited the city, a
year-on-year increase of 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The environmental card is part of the "green service"
introduced by the local hotel association this year. Other
activities launched include "Clean the Beach" and "Protecting
Every Piece of Coral."
</P>
<P>
The card has been favorably received by most tourists, with
some even writing down on the card that the bed-sheets and
pillowcases did not need to be changed.
</P>
<P>
The green service has already produced results. One of the
hotels has announced that it has reduced wastewater by 30
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
