<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of China OKs Loans for Satellite-Launching Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of China (BOC) today
agreed to extend 1.5 billion yuan in loans to assist the country's
effort to launch more international commercial satellites.
</P>
<P>
The recipient of the loan, in export seller's credits, is the
China Great Wall Industry Corp., China's sole firm engaged in
satellite-launching services and international satellite
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Part of the funds are exempt from guarantee, something that
makes it easier for the corporation to more flexibly meet the
requirements of customers in satellite-launching services.
</P>
<P>
The BOC has issued 7.3 billion yuan in loans to Great Wall
since 1990, supporting the launching of 15 satellites.
</P>
<P>
Great Wall has signed long-term cooperative agreements with
Hughes Aircraft Corp., the largest supplier of commercial
satellites in the world, and with Loral Space Systems, another
major satellite supplier in the United States. Great Wall plans to
launch 15 international commercial satellites in the next few
years.
</P>
<P>
In another measurement, the BOC has extended 26 billion yuan and
500 million U.S. dollars in export seller's credits since the
early 1980s to support China's exports of machinery and
electronics products.
</P>
<P>
To help counter the mounting effects of the Asian financial
crisis, the BOC will continue to lend great support to Chinese
exporters and to high-tech enterprises, a bank official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
