<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> LPG Fuel For Buses In Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua)-- Sixty buses using gasoline and
liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) appeared on Beijing's streets
Wednesday in densely-populated districts.
</P>
<P>
The new buses have LPG cylinders and another fuel system inside
and drivers can easily switch between the two.
</P>
<P>
More alternative fuel buses will be put into use in Beijing in
next several months because of growing environmental
consciousness. The Beijing Public Transit Co. plans to refit 1,000
buses by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Although the numbers are still small when compared with
Beijing's 1.3 million motor vehicles, buses produce the most
serious pollution.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has only a fifth of the number of motor vehicles of
similarly-sized cities in the developed countries, but the amount
of exhaust gas from its vehicle is three to five times that of
other cities and its heavy vehicle emissions have earned Beijing a
prominent place among the world's top 10 polluted cities.
</P>
<P>
Industry experts say that an LPG-powered vehicle puts out 92
percent less carbon monoxide than a gasoline vehicle for the same
power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 200 Ugandans Face Starvation After Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Some 200 people in the flooded
areas of Lake Kyoga, 200 to 300 kms north of Uganda's capital
Kampala, now face starvation after floods destroyed their food
crops.
</P>
<P>
The floods, which started three months ago, forced the worried
local population to buy surviving food from Lira district to the
north of the lake, the New Vision daily reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report said some two-kilometer-long roads had been cut off
by the flooding water and that people had to use canoes to cross
the flooded area.
</P>
<P>
John Nasasira, the Minister of Works, Housing and
Communication, who is on a two-day tour of feeder roads, railway
stations and post offices in the district, was quoted as assuring
the residents that the floating masses that have been blocking
the River Nile will be removed soon.
</P>
<P>
The overflow of the lake water is caused by a mass of sudds
that have blocked the Nile's exit from Lake Kyoga into Albert
Nile at Moone Landing site in the last couple of months.
</P>
<P>
The flooding has displaced over 15,000 people in the
neighboring districts. It also exerted much adverse influence on
fishing activities.
</P>
<P>
An Egyptian team of experts have come to help remove the
blockage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
