<HEADLINE> Anti-Flood Efforts Intensify in Northeast China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 14 (Xinhua) -- One million civilians and
soldiers have been mobilized for a round-the-clock fight against
China's worst flooding on the Nenjiang and Songhua rivers
in the northernmost province of Heilongjiang.
</P>
<P>
At 8 a.m. today, the water level on the Songhua River at Harbin,
the provincial capital, rose as high as 119.15 meters, with a
water flow of 8,890 cubic meters per second.
</P>
<P>
Due to the severe situation, Harbin, also a leading industrial
and grain production center, set a curfew on several sections of
the Songhua River embankments.
</P>
<P>
Eight working teams have been dispatched to the
worst-affected areas to help with evacuation and relief work.
</P>
<P>
In Qiqihar, the city hardest hit by the Nenjiang River deluge,
250,000 people began fortifying the major embankment and 4,000
participated in protecting the Yinghe River Reservoir at
Gannan County.
</P>
<P>
The number of anti-flood fighters in Daqing City, where China's
largest oilfield is located, has exceeded 200,000.
</P>
<P>
The efforts have helped move more than 400,000 water-besieged
people to safe locations with no deaths reported, and consumed 12
million cubic meters of stone and earth plus more than 14.3
million sand bags. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
