<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Gains Economic, Financial Clout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Accelerated market reforms have
effectively assisted the aim of Shanghai to be an international
economic, financial and trade center, according to Mayor Xu
Kuangdi.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's gross domestic product (GDP) has grown at an average
of 13.8 percent in the last five years, 5.9 percent higher than
the average for all of the 1980s and 2-to-4 percent higher than
the national figure during the same period, Xu told Chinese
scientists and overseas scientists of Chinese origin attending a
recent international seminar.
</P>
<P>
Based on the current exchange rate, Shanghai's per capita GDP
has reached 3,000 U.S. dollars, the highest among all Chinese
provinces and municipalities.
</P>
<P>
In recent years such sectors as finance, commerce, trade,
transportation, communication and real estate in Shanghai have
developed rapidly, turning Shanghai into an open and
multi-functional economic center from a pure industrial and
commercial city.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Shanghai's securities, foreign exchange, technology,
metal and commodity futures markets have attained considerable
size, Xu said.
</P>
<P>
He said that mandatory government orders have given way to
market forces in the distribution of resources, with the prices of
more than 95 percent of all industrial products and more than 90
percent of all production materials and farm produce determined by
the market.
</P>
<P>
A social security system that covers old age, unemployment and
medical care has been established and covers basically the whole
society, the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Shanghai today has increasingly close ties
with the world economy, adding that imports and exports through
the Shanghai port totaled nearly 60 billion U.S. dollars last
year, about 20 percent of the national figure.
</P>
<P>
Official figures also indicate that more than 10,000
overseas-funded enterprises have opened in Shanghai, with paid-in
overseas investment hitting 21 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Xu said that Shanghai aims to have built a framework for an
international economic, financial and trade center by the start of
the next century.
</P>
<P>
This will help boost economic growth in the Yangtze River Delta
and the Yangtze River Valley as a whole, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
