<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shandong's Power Industry Marks 100th Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, August 14 (Xinhua) -- After 100 years of both slow and
rapid expansion, the power sector of east China's Shandong
Province has become one of the most developed in China.
</P>
<P>
Shandong now has the single largest independent power grid
among all of China's provinces, municipalities and autonomous
regions. In 1996, it became the first in China to make electricity
accessible to every household. Shandong's daily power generation
exceeds 200 million kilowatts/hour (kwh), about the total of 1949,
the year when new China was founded.
</P>
<P>
Shandong's power sector started in 1898 when invading Germans
installed two diesel-engine, 50-horsepower generators to supply
electricity for German military facilities and institutions.
</P>
<P>
In the next five decades, the power industry of Shandong
advanced at a snail's pace due to invasion by several big Western
powers and the chaos caused by years of war.
</P>
<P>
However, Shandong's power sector has developed by leaps and
bounds since China launched its market economy reforms in the late
1970s, with annual power generation increasing by an average of 10
percent each year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, Shandong's installed power generation
capacity totaled 16.5 million kilowatts (kw) while actual yearly
power generation hit 84 billion kwh.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Shandong's power grid includes five power plants
with an installed capacity of more than one million kw each. The
Zouxian Power Plant in Zouxian County is the largest power plant
on the Chinese mainland with an installed capacity of 2.4 million
kw.
</P>
<P>
Liu Zhenya, director of the Shandong Provincial Power Industry
Bureau, said the size of Shandong's power sector is large overall,
but that the province's power generation and consumption in per
capita terms are still at a relatively low level compared with
many other parts of China.
</P>
<P>
Starting now, Shandong will increase its effort to develop
power resources and build and renovate the power grid, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Shandong's installed power generation capacity should exceed 20
million kw by the end of this century and annual power generation
is expected to reach 110 billion kwh, he added.
</P>
<P>
By year 2005, the two figures are expected to hit 30 million kw
and 150 billion kwh, respectively, Liu said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
