<HEADLINE> 9,851 People in Inner Mongolia Remain Stranded by Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, August 14 (Xinhua) -- A total of 24,245 people stranded
by floods in the eastern part of north China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region have been moved to higher ground.
</P>
<P>
However, another 9,851 are still believed stranded in flooded
areas. Efforts are under way to evacuate them, an official from
the Regional Flood Control Headquarters said here today.
</P>
<P>
Unusually big floods on the Nenjiang River have hit 60 counties
and cities in eastern Inner Mongolia since August 8, leaving
410,000 people homeless. Officers and soldiers of the Chinese
People's Liberation Army and armed police rushed to flooded areas
and worked five days and nights to evacuate the stranded people.
</P>
<P>
The latest information from the regional flood control
headquarters said the water level in the main stream of the
Nenjiang River that flows on the eastern part of the region has
continued to rise, and the Chuo'er River, a tributary of the
Nenjiang, has been swollen to a dangerous level.
</P>
<P>
By 8 a.m. today, the Jiangqiao Hydrological Station on the
Nenjiang River recorded a water level of 142.04 meters and a water
flow of 12,700 cubic meters per second, but the water level is
expected to climb to 143 meters and the water flow to 15,000 cubic
meters per second or more.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhan, deputy secretary of the regional Committee of the
Communist Party of China, consulted with a newly formed
professional team consisting of a group of water control experts
about possible counter-measures.
</P>
<P>
To avoid fresh flooding, the water control experts have
proposed solidifying the one-kilometer-long section of embankment
built along the Chuo'er River, raising the existing
embankment' height, and using tarpaulins to protect the embankment
from wave action.
</P>
<P>
The counter-measures are now being carefully executed in
Hinggan League and Jalaid Banner, said local sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
