<HEADLINE> Turkish Stock Market Tumbles Over Russian Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's Istanbul Stock Exchange
plunged 6.76 percent in heavy trading on Thursday to 3,311.60
points, in reaction to the economic turmoil in Russia, a main
trade partner of Turkey, local newspaper Daily News reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Istanbul Stock Exchange National-Index Thursday lost 242.2
points following the reports that the Moscow Stock Exchange's
Central Index had dived 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the past four trading days, the market witnessed three days
of decline. It dipped by 5.81 percent on Monday, followed by a
further 7.35 percent tumble on Tuesday. The market only regained
some grounds by surging 3.55 percent on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Moscow Stock Exchange index slid
after Hungarian-born leading investor George Soros told the
Financial Times on Wednesday that Russia should devalue its
currency by 15 to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Daily News quoted Turkish investors as saying that a collapse
of the Russian economy could cripple hundreds of Turkish
companies with investment in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Scores of blue-chip Turkish companies doing business with
Russia are listed on the Istanbul Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Stock markets around the world have been reeling as a result
of the growing Asian economic crisis, which began last summer
with the collapse of the currencies and stocks in Thailand,
Malaysia and Indonesia and then spread to other regions.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government's possible sharp devaluation of the
Turkish Lira against Western currencies has also prompted
investors to sell shares on the market.
</P>
<P>
However, Turkish Central Bank Governor Gazi Ercel on Thursday
denied reports that the government would devalue the Turkish
lira, saying the bank was able to avoid a major devaluation
because it had accumulated 26 billion U.S. dollars of foreign
reserves to overcome the present crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
