<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Residents near Breached River Section Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JIUJIANG, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Residents living in areas
inundated by floods coming through a 60-meter breach on the
Yangtze River's main embankment have returned to their homes since
the breach was blocked on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
From the highest point of the city dike which stands 24 meters
above sea level, residents could be seen Friday going into their
houses 100 meters away from the breach.
</P>
<P>
People living in areas far behind the embankment returned from
temporary huts Thursday afternoon, said Ding Xinfa, an anti-flood
director.
</P>
<P>
In the nearest house, where floodwater has receded 1 meter from
the doorstep, a woman was in front of her house washing wooden
furniture stained by mud.
</P>
<P>
Next door a man and woman were having their meal on a
short-legged table. Clothes and bed sheets were fluttering in the
wind in front of the houses near the embankment.
</P>
<P>
Officers and soldiers of the Chinese People's Liberation Army
today poured 1,000 cubic meters of stone and clay at the site to
reinforce the framework blocking the breach. Efforts to prevent
leakage of water from the make-shift dike are under way.
</P>
<P>
The breach occurred on Aug. 7 at the Jiujiang section in east
China's Jiangxi Province. The 60-meter breach was cemented
completely on Wednesday after five days of strenuous work. More
than 3,000 residents had been evacuated from the region soon after
the breach was discovered.
</P>
<P>
The water level at the Jiujiang section had dropped to 22.61
meters by 8 a.m. today.
</P>
<P>
Water conservation experts are considering whether or not to
build a third defense dam in Jiujiang.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 200 reports from 95 media organizations --
including those from Hong Kong, Taiwan and countries in other
parts of the world -- are writing flood stories in the
city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
