<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Continue Practice of Public Notaries in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) - The Chinese Ministry of Justice
and the Hong Kong government will continue the current practice of
entrusting public notaries in Hong Kong to promote economic and
civil contracts between Hong Kong and the mainland, a ministry
official said today.
</P>
<P>
At a recent national conference, Xiao Yishun, director of the
Public Notary Department of the ministry, said the ministry has
commissioned 200 notaries in Hong Kong by the end of 1997 since
the system was established in 1980. They have notarized 480,000
agreements so far.
</P>
<P>
These notarized documents are related to almost all civil and
economic issues, including marriage, inheritance and adoption, as
well as investments, trusts, real estate and trade, according to
the director.
</P>
<P>
"This practice makes it possible that a notarized document can
be accepted in the two different legal systems of Hong Kong and
the mainland, reducing the time and costs for repeated
confirmation of notarized documents and benefiting clients," Xiao
said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the 17-year-old system has been supported by both
Hong Kong and mainland residents.
</P>
<P>
The system was originally initiated to promote the smooth
return of Hong Kong to the motherland. Because of its important
roles, top Chinese officials said that the system should remain
after the handover and that the new government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region said it will support the system as
well.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Justice, all the public notaries
on commission must be prestigious lawyers in Hong Kong and that
the qualification confirmation process is complicated and
rigorous. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
