<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, August 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA -- Ethiopian Finance Minister Sufian Ahmed
announced Thursday that his government has collected 6.7 billion
Birr (about 957 million U.S. dollars) from tax and non-tax
revenues in 1997/98 budget year, 95 percent of the original target
of seven billion Birr (about one billion U.S. dollars).
(Ethiopia-Revenue)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko Thursday said
there have been no financial causes for the current crisis on the
Russian financial market and it has been caused by psychological
reasons. (Russia-Financial Crisis)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's current account surplus posted a year-on-year
52.9 percent rise in the January to June period, to hit 7573.3
billion yen (about 51.5 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
This marked the third straight half-year period of increase,
the Japanese Finance Ministry said Thursday. (Japan-Current
Account-Surplus)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Bank of Japan (BOJ) Governor Masaru Hayami said on
Thursday that Japan's economy is still deteriorating generally,
and an immediate transition to a self-sustained recovery can
hardly be expected. (Japan-Economy-Worsening)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
KIEV -- Ukraine's grain output this year will be down 10
percent from last year's 35.47 million tons, said Yuriy Luzan,
associated minister of Agriculture-Industry Complexes Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But he predicted that grain exports will total about 3 million
tons, about two times the figure of 1997. (Ukraine-Grain-Output)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
COLOMBO -- The International Monetary Fund (IMF) has hailed Sri
Lanka's stability and economic growth in the face of acute
financial turmoil in Southeast Asia, the official Daily News
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The IMF sources were quoted as saying that the challenge now,
according to a review of the Sri Lankan economy by the IMF, is to
tighten fiscal and monetary policies to carry out reform of the
financial sector. (Sri Lanka-IMF)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Commercial vehicle sales in the Philippines dropped
38.7 percent to 26,995 units in the first seven months of this
year compared with the year-ago level, according to the latest
industry figures. (Philippines-Vehicle Sales)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazilian exports to Asia went down 20.39
percent in the first half of this year compared to the same period
of 1997, down from 3.672 billion dollars to 2.923 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Exports to Malaysia, Indonesia, South Korea, Philippines and
Thailand dropped 48.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Sales to Japan, Brazilian biggest importer in Asia, registered
only 1.157 billion dollars in the first half of the year, against
1.467 billion dollars in the same period of last year.
(Brazil-Export-Asia) 
