<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Expects 5.8 Pct GDP Growth This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka is expected to net an
5.8 percent growth of the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) at the end
of this year.
</P>
<P>
This is revealed in a study conducted by the Bank of Ceylon
(Sri Lanka) which attributes this success to improvements in
economic fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
The lately study says that the impact of this on business
confidence augurs well for Sri Lanka's economy despite the
unfavorable international economic scenario and the civil war.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, the agricultural, manufacturing and
construction, banking, insurance and real estate sectors will grow
significantly at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Paddy output is expected to increase significantly over last
year.  The continued spectacular performance of tea and the
rebound in minor agricultural export crops project an increase of
3.8 percent in agricultural output.
</P>
<P>
Tea output will reach the 280 million kilogram mark on the
basis of improved cultural practices and improved management
systems.
</P>
<P>
Donor confidence in Sri Lanka enabled the country to receive
700 million U.S. dollars for 1998/99 which is 80 million dollars
more than expected.
</P>
<P>
Textile and garments, the leading sub-sector in the export
sector, recorded a 10 percent growth in terms of U.S. dollars
during the first four months of the year. With improvements the
industry is likely to grow further.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's economy grew by 5.8 percent in the first quarter of
the year despite an increase of eight billion rupees (121 million
dollars) for defense, Deputy Finance Minister G.L. Peiris Thursday
told newsmen.
</P>
<P>
The country has 38 million U.S. dollars in foreign exchange
reserves, enough for five months' imports, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, the global economic environment is unlikely to
continue to be favorable, mainly due to the current Asian
financial crisis. This year the country's economic growth will be
low compared with last year, the minister pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka enjoyed a growth of 6.4 percent in 1997, up from 3.8
percent in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
