<HEADLINE> Pak PM Urges India to Negotiate on Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif Friday urged India to return to the negotiating table to
resolve the Kashmir dispute between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
India could not sustain its repression in held Kashmir, and "it
has to return to negotiating table to resolve this issue," Sharif
said while addressing a flay-hoisting ceremony here Friday morning
to mark the country's 51st Independence Day.
</P>
<P>
He vowed "unflinching support" to the Kashmiri people till they
get their right to self-determination.
</P>
<P>
"We are compelled to raise voice in support of our Kashmiri
brethren who have been enduring the inhuman atrocities of
occupation forces for the last many years," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The nuclear factor in South Asia has necessitated the need for
solution of Kashmir problem," he noted, referring to the
tit-for-tat nuclear tests by India and Pakistan in May.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister made it clear that Pakistan is a
peace-loving nation and does not harbor aggressive designs against
any country.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the confidence that soon Pakistan would emerge as
a prosperous and developed nation on the map of the world.
</P>
<P>
He said, tremendous external pressure was exerted on Pakistan
after its nuclear tests, "more sanctions were imposed on us, all
sorts of economic pulls and pushes were used against us."
</P>
<P>
However, he said he was proud that the Pakistani nation is
facing the difficulties courageously.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan cannot compromise no its defense. If Pakistan
succumbed to international pressure these sanctions would be
lifted immediately but we are determined not to bow before these
pressures," he said.
</P>
<P>
These sanctions, he said, have helped Pakistan move towards
self-reliance and stand on its own feet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
