<HEADLINE> State-Owned Steel Plant Privatized in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- A state-owned Myanmar steel plant
has been transferred to local private entrepreneurs for continuous
effective operation to promote the plant's production.
</P>
<P>
The Ywama Steel Plant of No.3 Myanmar Mining Enterprise in
Yangon, handed over on Thursday, is the largest industry
privatized since the country formed the Privatization Commission
in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
The plant is also the initial venture in Myanmar, jointly
participated by successful national entrepreneurs,
Lieutenant-General Khin Nyunt, first secretary of the Myanmar
State Peace and Development Council, was quoted by Friday's
official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar as saying.
</P>
<P>
Khin Nyunt, who supervised the transfer arrangement, urged the
entrepreneurs to strive for emergence of cartels of heavy
industries and conglomerates in Myanmar as in other Asian
nations.
</P>
<P>
Since Myanmar announced in January 1995 the first-phase plan of
 privatization of 51 state-owned economic enterprises (SEEs) which
include different processing and manufacturing factories, cinemas
and livestock breeding farms, the privatization process has been
underway in various forms including auctioning and leasing out
the SEEs or establishing joint ventures with local and foreign
entrepreneurs or operating either under buy-back or counter-trade
system.
</P>
<P>
Up to July since the beginning of this year, about 140
state-run cinemas, some 42 factories and two livestock breeding
farms in the country have been designated to be sold through
competitive bidding.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than two dozen state-owned saw mills have been
reportedly privatized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
