<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Stock Exchange Goes Automatic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Dhaka Stock Exchange, Bangladesh's
premier bourse, went automatic Thursday, ending 44 years of floor
trading.
</P>
<P>
"The investors will regain their confidence and come back to
the market, if discipline is maintained strictly," Finance
Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria said while inaugurating the automated
trading system, the national Financial Express reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister formally inaugurated the computerized
trading system through purchasing 50 shares by putting the switch
on from a local hotel.
</P>
<P>
Terming the system a "giant step" towards ensuring transparency
in capital market operations in the country, Kibria said it would
help the market greatly regain investors' confidence, as "the
market cannot be manipulated so easily."
</P>
<P>
He urged stock brokers and traders to abide by the rules and
regulations. "Once you become habituated to the regulatory system,
you will be able to do business at ease and comfort," he said.
</P>
<P>
More reforms were needed to ensure transparency in the capital
market, including introduction of a central depository system,
strengthening of the existing accounting and auditing system and
correct disclosure by listed companies, according to the finance
minister.
</P>
<P>
"If you do the things in the right way, the market will bounce
back by its own way," since "confidence cannot be brought back
artificially," he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the exchange authorities to increase its membership
with a view to injecting new blood into it.
</P>
<P>
There are two stock exchange markets in Bangladesh at present -
the Dhaka Stock Exchange and the Chittagong Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
