<HEADLINE> IMF Hails Sri Lanka's Stability, Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 14 (Xinhua) -- the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) has hailed Sri Lanka's stability and economic growth in the
face of acute financial turmoil in Southeast Asia, the official
Daily News reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The IMF sources were quoted as saying that the challenge now,
according to a review of the Sri Lankan economy by the IMF, is to
tighten fiscal and monetary policies to carry out reform of the
financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has commended the authorities for maintaining macro
economic stability in 1997 despite the continued civil strife and
a difficult regional environment and for making steady progress in
addressing structural weaknesses, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Bucking a regional trend towards stagnation, Sri Lanka enjoyed
a growth of 6.4 percent from 3.8 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Overall growth was supported by a strong recovery in
agricultural production, higher exports of garments and textiles
and continued good performance in the services sector, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The broadening in the tax base has been recommended together
with revenue sharing measures to reduce reliance on sharp cuts in
social services and infrastructure spending, they noted.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has warned that the financial sector weaknesses in Sri
Lanka including the relationship between state and the banking
sector needed to be promptly identified and corrected.
</P>
<P>
In particular the IMF has called for the separation of the
commercial and non-commercial activities of the two state banks
and for their privatization as soon as possible, the sources
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
