<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Economists Forecast U.S. Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.S economy is expected
to grow by 3.4 percent in 1998, despite surging trade deficits and
the impact of the Asian financial crisis, according to the
consensus forecast by 19 leading Wall Street economists.
</P>
<P>
Bright prospects for the rest of 1998 are lower interest rates,
strong employment growth and gains in real disposable personal
income. These factors will continue to fuel the housing sector,
said the report published by the Bank of America on Thursday. The
economists also projected the trends of the U.S. economy in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Most of the panel believe the Federal Reserve will hold
interest rates steady through the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the U.S. economy will continue to grow at a good
pace, with the real gross domestic product (GDP) expected to
average 3.4 percent in 1998. At the same time, inflation, as
measured by the Consumer Price Index, is expected to average 1.7
percent in 1998, and the unemployment rate is expected to average
4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
There are also bad news for sectors of the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
"A majority of our panelists believe that economic conditions
in Southeast Asia have yet to bottom, which could continue to
negatively impact U.S. exports to Asia," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The panel also believe that consumer confidence and capital
spending remain critical to U.S. growth prospects for the rest of
this year and into the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The economists project that the U.S. trade deficit will balloon
to 244 billion U.S. dollars in 1998. They expect corporate profits
to increase by just 1.8 percent, and industrial production to grow by
3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the economists seem more optimistic than they
were when they were surveyed last month. They said the
U.S. economy will grow at a modest pace in 1999 and predicted a
probability of 36 percent -- up two percentage points from last
month's survey -- that that would be the case.
</P>
<P>
The panel also predicted a probability of 29 percent that the
economy would be slowing down by next August. In addition, the
panel believed there is only a 20 percent probability the
U.S. economy will be booming a year from now, while there is a 15
percent probability that the economy will be experiencing
stagflation by next August -- a stagnating economy accompanied by
rising inflation.
</P>
<P>
During 1999, the economists predicted that inflation will rise
slightly to 2.3 percent and unemployment will remain low at 4.6
percent. Once again, the trade picture in 1999 will remain a
problem, with the trade deficit expected to exceed 284.9 billion
dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Praises Accord on Holocaust-era Assets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Thursday praised the agreement reached between Swiss
banks and Holocaust survivors and heirs of the victims while local
U.S. financial officers cancel plans to sanction the Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides demonstrated understanding, flexibility and
determination in reaching a settlement that... will bring long
delayed justice to Holocaust victims and their families," Clinton
said in a statement issued by the White House.
</P>
<P>
The deal, hammered out in a U.S. district court in Brooklyn,
New York, ended a three-year period of uncertainty as banks first
opposed, then finally conceded to an agreement to settle claims on
the missing assets.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday, U.S. financial officers in New York canceled
plans to impose sanctions on the banks and other Swiss businesses.
</P>
<P>
"We are canceling our program of sanctions," New York City
Comptroller Alan Hevesi, head of a panel of 900 financial officers
from towns, cities and states across America, told a news
conference in New York.
</P>
<P>
"We also recognize that Holocaust issues remain with us and we
call on the Swiss government to join in spirit with this
agreement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hevesi noted that other European countries aside from
Switzerland had "moral obligations" regarding the return of money
and valuables deposited in banks by Jews before, during and after
World War Two or looted by Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congress has legislation to create a commission to
examine the role of American banks on similar issues.
</P>
<P>
Despite the administration's opposition, the local financial
officers planned to impose sanctions on Swiss banks from September
1 unless the banks agreed to settle the claims of Jewish groups
and Holocaust survivors.
</P>
<P>
Hevesi announced the plan on July 1 after a breakdown in
negotiations when the Swiss offered a 600 million U.S. dollars
settlement while Jewish groups wanted 1.5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
About 20 states and 30 cities had been preparing potentially
harmful sanctions.
</P>
<P>
New York State Comptroller H. Carl McCall told the same news
conference on Thursday that he was "delighted" to call off the
sanctions before they could take effect.
</P>
<P>
In California, State Treasurer Matt Fong, another leader of the
financial officer's group, also announced the lift of all
restrictions against his state doing business with Swiss banks
because of the settlement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
