<HEADLINE> Jakarta Military Seeks Help From Foreign Groups to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian capital city
military is soliciting help from foreign groups in its effort to
identify people spreading rumors on the Internet of renewed riots
in Jakarta, the Jakarta Post reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"To detect (those responsible for) rumors on the Internet,
we've asked the assistance of foreign parties," Jakarta Military
Commander Maj. Gen. Djadja Suparman told reporters Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Djadja refused to elaborate on what he meant by "foreign
parties", but said a joint investigation was ongoing.
</P>
<P>
"We have not yet detected the rumormongers. The investigation
will take quite a long time and there will be many people to
testify. So, please be patient," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to National Police Detective Corps Commander Maj.
Gen. Da'i Bachtiar, his personnel have also been ordered to
investigate the rumors, which have spread throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Rumors have it that unrest will occur ahead of the August 17
Independence Day celebration.
</P>
<P>
Although police consider the rumors to be phony, security
officers have taken measures to anticipate any possible
disturbances.
</P>
<P>
"We're closely monitoring the current situation and at the same
time seeking the perpetrators, who have transmitted the rumors via
leaflets and the Internet," Da'i said.
</P>
<P>
Security has been noticeably strengthened this week, with fully
armed soldiers patrolling the capital in trucks and guarding
public buildings.
</P>
<P>
Security in particular areas has also been beefed up. Residents
have also been asked to tighten security in their respective
neighborhood and business areas.
</P>
<P>
According to an officer, a number of streets around National
Monument Square in central Jakarta will be temporarily closed next
Monday during flag-hoisting ceremonies in commemoration of the
country's 53rd Independence Day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
