<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientist Warns of Possible Red Tide at Yangtze River Mouth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, August 14 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese scientist has warned
that the long-term flooding on the Yangtze River is likely to
result in a red tide at the river's mouth.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Jingzhong, a professor with the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, said that the floods will lead to a surplus of nutrients
at the mouth of the river.
</P>
<P>
"There has already been a surplus of nutrients in the region,"
he said. "Survey results show that the content of nitrogen in the
river in the 1990s is six times as much as that in the 1960s."
</P>
<P>
The big floods will bring muddy water rich in nitrogen and
phosphorus to the river mouth, worsening the problem of nutrient
surplus in the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
The scorching weather this summer has also provided a conducive
environment for a red tide, Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, at the river's mouth, endured temperatures exceeding
38 degrees Celsius for four consecutive days through Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Zhou warned that the biological, physical, chemical and weather
conditions are conducive to a red tide. "Relevant departments
should increase monitoring and take immediate measures once red
tides take place so as to reduce losses," he said.
</P>
<P>
Red tides are caused by a heavy buildup of planktons that
release toxic substances which consume oxygen and suffocate fish.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
