<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina's industrial output in the first half
of this year grew six percent, the Argentine Ministry of Industry,
Commerce and Mining reported.
</P>
<P>
Motor vehicle output increased 16.9 percent compared to the
same period in 1997, while steel, aluminum, and cement rose 3.9
percent, 17.2 percent, and 12.4 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Electricity consumption went up in July seven percent compared
to the same month of 1997, and industrial gas rose 7.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The 1998-1999 coffee harvest will amount to 33.95
million 60-kilo bags, an 80 percent increase over the previous
year thanks to good weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
Brazil produced 22.5 million bags of coffee in 1997 and
exported 14.6 million bags, according to official estimates which
also put this year's exports at 15.6 million bags.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rican tax revenue amounted to just over one
billion dollars in the first seven months of this year, which
represents a 24.6 percent increase over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Data released by the Finance Ministry shows that of this total,
customs contributed 488.4 million dollars, followed by sales with
181.9 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Income tax was third with 179.7 million dollars, and consumer
tax was fourth with 70.6 million dollars, while revenue from other
taxes was 75.6 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Colombia is suffering one of its worst
years in the oil industry despite the good production of its
installations, as the prices of crude and by-products continue to
drop.
</P>
<P>
Colombia is losing 3.20 dollars per barrel, according to the
figures for this year, which means that by December it will have
lost 320 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The United States Department of Agriculture (USDA)
will create in Brazil a free zone for the export of citrus fruits
to U.S. markets, at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The USDA will have to request a provisional authorization to
create in Brazil the first free zone in the state of Piaui, in the
northeast for the export of citrus fruits to the United States.
</P>
<P>
It was known that with the creation of the free zone in Piaui,
rich in the production of lemons, the cultivation of this fruit
for the international market will be promoted in this country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
