<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Readjust Water Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Water charges in Beijing,
capital of China, will be averagely raised from 0.92 yuan (0.11 US
dollars) to 1.22 yuan (0.15 US dollars) per ton, according to a
plan reported by China Daily today.
</P>
<P>
The plan is now under the approval of the State Development
Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
This will be the second water price rate adjustment this year, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has long suffered from a shortage of water. The per
capita possession of water resources in this city is less than 300
tons, only one-eighth of the national average.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, water used for restaurants, the
entertainment industry and washing cars will be increased from 1
yuan (0.12 U.S. dollars) to 1.5 yuan (0.18 U.S.dollars) per ton.
</P>
<P>
The charge for the water for other uses will increase from 0.7
yuan (0.08 U.S. dollars) to 1 yuan per ton.
</P>
<P>
A hearing concerning the readjustment was held on July 21 by
the Beijing Pricing Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The increase in water charges aims at encouraging Beijingers to
use water economically.  
</P>
</TEXT>
