<HEADLINE> Security Beefed Up in Several Indonesian Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Security has been beefed up in
some of Indonesia's cities prior to August 17 Independence Day
celebrations, local press reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
In the country's second largest city of Surabaya, security
personnel were seen guarding a number of shopping malls and
buildings.
</P>
<P>
Brawijaya Regional Military Commander Maj. Gen. Djoko Subroto,
who oversees security in East Java province, met with 300 Moslem
ulemas Thursday to ask for their help in maintaining calm and
order.
</P>
<P>
He called on them to tell their respective communities that the
 authorities were fully in control of the situation and not to be
agitated by rumors.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the week, Djoko also met with members of the ethnic
Chinese community in Surabaya and urged them not to listen to
vicious rumors of impending violence.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, there has been a reported increase in flight
reservations out of Surabaya for the next three days.
</P>
<P>
In Semarang, capital of Central Java province, more security
forces were put on alert to guard the city.
</P>
<P>
City police chief Col. Soenarko told reporters that security
had been beefed up since Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Undercover teams comprised of selected officers have also been
stationed at trouble-prone spots," he said.
</P>
<P>
Local military commander Lt. Col. Supriyanto called on the
public to participate in safeguarding their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
Reports of unrest have already surfaced in West Java province.
Soldiers had to fire warning shots to disperse hundreds of people
late Wednesday after they looted several ethnic Chinese-owned
shops and burned a discotheque in two West Java towns.
</P>
<P>
In Labuan, 150 kilometers southwest of Jakarta, mobs looted
three shops after a customer argued with a storekeeper over the
price of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
Later that evening a mob in the nearby town of Serang burned a
hotel discotheque suspected of harboring prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
The mobs were dispersed only after two platoons of the Army's
Special Force approached the site, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
In the holiday resort island of Bali, Deputy Governor Ahim
Abdurahim told reporters that the island had been "invaded" by
Chinese-Indonesians seeking refuge from possible unrest.
</P>
<P>
"For those who feel unsafe in their place of domicile, it would
be natural for them to pick Bali as an alternative place of
residence," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
