<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Players Association Withdraws Unfair Labor Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The NBA Players Association
today withdrew its unfair labor practice charge against the NBA,
according to a report from New York.
</P>
<P>
The NBPA filed the labor complaint before the National Labor
Relations Board, claiming the league unilaterally changed the
terms and conditions of employment for the players when it
instituted a lockout.
</P>
<P>
However, hours before the complaint was to be heard by NLRB
regional director Daniel Silverman, the Players Association opted
to withdraw the charge.
</P>
<P>
"This is obviously a defeat for the union's strategy of
litigation instead of negotiation," said NBA Deputy Commissioner
Russ Granik. "The players must now recognize that the NBA lockout
is completely lawful, and the only way it will end is when the
parties sit down and reach a deal that is fair to both sides."
</P>
<P>
The union cited time and expenses as the reasons for
withdrawing the complaint. "After consulting with the NBPA, it
was determined that the players would not be able to achieve
relief as swiftly as would be necessary to justify the effort and
expense of litigation," said Pete Stergois, outside counsel to
the NBPA.
</P>
<P>
Despite the withdrawal of the unfair labor charge, NBPA
executive director Billy Hunter made it clear today that the
players remain unified against the lockout. The union currently
has a grievance before arbitrator John Feerick requesting the
guaranteed contracts of players be paid during the lockout. The
grievance hearing is scheduled for August 24-25.
</P>
<P>
On August 5, the only serious collective bargaining session
since the lockout was held, but ended with owners walking out on
the players Association. No further talks have been scheduled so
far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
