<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Speeding Up Human Genome Project (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- China plans to inject at least
250 million yuan (30 million U.S. dollars) within the next three
years to support human genome studies.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the project said they will engage in research
on genes related to major diseases.
</P>
<P>
Two big human genome research centers in Beijing and Shanghai,
which are jointly sponsored by the government and businesses, will
soon carry out studies with a focus on identifying and cloning
genes related to liver cancer, diabetes, high blood pressure and
other diseases.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 laboratories across the country are involved in
the sequencing and analysis of human genes.
</P>
<P>
China's investment in the human genome project (HGP) will
increase to 300 million yuan (36 million U.S. dollars) by 2000, 10
times the total investment up to 1996, said Professor Qiang Boqin,
vice-president of the Chinese Academy of Medical Sciences.
</P>
<P>
"It shows at least in one dimension that China is trying to
speed up its human genome studies," Qiang said.
</P>
<P>
However, the greatly increased funding may not narrow the gap
between China's HGP research and the world's advanced level in a
short period of time, experts said, adding that the only way China
can make a bigger contribution to the world HGP project lies in
the study of disease-related genes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Speeding Up Human Genome Project (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The world's HGP research started in the United States in 1990,
and should be finished by 2005. Under the project, scientists are
trying to identify all the 100,000 human genes and interpret their
genetic codes.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that only about 5 percent of human genes are
useful in the study of disease, which have attracted many medical
experts and received large amounts of money from pharmaceutical
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"Researchers in China hope that they can find 1,000 such genes
by the year 2001, and identify and clone the functional genes
linked to 5-to-10 major diseases," said Chen Zhu, director of the
Shanghai Human Genome Research Center.
</P>
<P>
Since the HGP started in China in 1993, Chinese scientists have
completed the study on the genome diversity of Han nationality
people, and 12 ethnic minority groups in China. Progress has also
been made in the study of genes related to leukemia, and
esophagus, liver and nosopharygeal cancers.
</P>
<P>
Chen said the human genome studies in China, where there is a
large variety of diseases, will take the identifying of genes
related to diseases with a high incidence rate and major hazard as
its major direction.
</P>
<P>
China will try to follow the latest development of human genome
research in the world, while improving the research and
international exchanges on ethical problems related to genetic and
biological science, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0210 </DOCNO>
