<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peters Dismissed as New Zealand Deputy PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Winston Peters has been
dismissed as New Zealand deputy prime minister and treasurer.
</P>
<P>
The dismissal of Peters was announced here Friday by New
Zealand Prime Minister Jenny Shipley in a press statement.
</P>
<P>
in the statement, Shipley said she had advised the
governor-general to dismiss Peters immediately from his
ministerial responsibilities as deputy prime minister and
treasurer. On her advice, the governor-general has appointed Bill
Birch to the office of treasurer. Birch will also continue as
minister of finance.
</P>
<P>
Shipley said she has set out the reasons for the dismissal in a
letter to Peters. In the letter, the New Zealand prime minister
said: "It is my view that you have shown a refusal to accept
Cabinet collective responsibility. Further, you have publicly
criticized Government policy regarding the sale of the Crown's
shareholding in Wellington Airport, and your actions and
statements regarding the sale were unacceptable. Further, your
unfounded allegations in the Parliament that I have breached some
alleged undertakings make it untenable for you to remain as a
Cabinet Minister."
</P>
<P>
Shipley said in the statement that she had the responsibility
to the country to ensure that the Cabinet was able to perform its
functions and duties in accordance with the important principle of
collective responsibility. "That is critical in maintaining public
confidence in executive decision-making and the reputation of New
Zealand," she said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also said that she had written to all other
ministers from New Zealand First, informing them that they would
retain their ministerial responsibility and asking each of them to
meet her and to give her a personal commitment that they
understand the obligations of collective responsibility and to
give her an undertaking they are willing to comply with those
obligations.
</P>
<P>
The latest public disputes between Shipley and Peters was
triggered by Peters' walkout of a special Cabinet meeting
Wednesday night as a decision was about to be taken to sell the
government's stake in the Wellington Airport. The walkout was
followed by an exchange of accusation of each other through the
local TV station and extraordinary scenes of acrimony between the
two in Parliament Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
