<HEADLINE> Italy Selling More Enterprises to Pay for Public Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Revenues from the sale of Italy's
public enterprises to slash its soaring public debt more than
trebled in 1997 over the previous year, the Audit Court said in a
report on the Treasury on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The privatization income amounted to 34.673 trillion lire (20
billion U.S. dollars), up 275 percent from 1996, when the total
9.226 trillion lire (5.3 billion dollars) marked a 10.4 percent
increase over 1995, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Large industries sold by the Italian government in 1997
included the petrochemicals group Eni, the San Paolo banking
group, Telecom and Seat, the yellow pages publisher of Italy's
former telecommunications utility Stet.
</P>
<P>
The selling of public enterprises became the government's most
important means of reducing public debt. Of the privatization
revenues in 1997, 24,6 trillion lire (14 billion dollars) would be
used to pay off public debt.
</P>
<P>
The Audit Court said that privatization revenues had so far
contributed some 60.624 trillion lire (35 billion dollars) to the
Public Debt Reduction Fund which was founded in 1994, including
some revenues available in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 revenues included 24.45 trillion lire (13.9 billion
dollars) from the first flotation of Telecom stocks, and five
trillion lire (2.8 billion dollars) from Eni2, or the second sale
of Eni shares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
