<HEADLINE> Feature: Uygur Teacher Says, 'I Believe I Can Fly' (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 14 (Xinhua) -- For several decades a Uygur teacher
in Turpan, a city in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, said he
has dreamed of flying his own plane in the blue sky as free as an
eagle.
</P>
<P>
Abdulla Kadir's dream has come true. In his self-made
airplanes, "Turpan No.1" and "Turpan No.2," Abdulla has already
made successful flights and "Turpan No.3" is nearly ready in his
grape-trellised yard.
</P>
<P>
Abdulla's house, in Munak Village of Turpan, resembles an
airplane museum. At the gate, the seven-meter "Turpan No.2" is
parked under a mulberry tree. In the yard, a newly made wing hangs
on a grape trellis and the unfinished project is lying on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
Abdulla, 41, a Uygur teacher at Xinjiang Turpan Normal School,
said that besides his own interests he was making planes for the
children.
</P>
<P>
"Turpan is still a quite closed place," he said. "Most children
here have never seen an airplane. Sometimes during class, when a
plane roared over the school, all the students rushed to the
windows and watched until it was out of sight. Thus I thought that
how wonderful that would be if there was a plane for children to
watch and touch."
</P>
<P>
Abdulla began building his first plane in 1986. With the
plane model and physical knowledge he gained from the university,
he finished the drawings of the plane after thousands of
calculations and tests.
</P>
<P>
The high cost of building planes was a problem for Abdulla, who
has to support a family of seven people on a salary of several
hundred yuan every month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
