<HEADLINE> Opposition Criticizes Costa Rican-Nicaraguan Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Costa Rican Social Democrat
opposition Thursday criticized the government's way of handling
relations with Nicaragua, which are considered tense at the moment.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentarians of the National Liberation Party accused the
government of sending the Costa Rican Public Security minister to
negotiate an agreement with the Nicaraguan defense minister.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed on July 30, regulates the transit of
Costa Rican police on the San Juan River border, which belongs to
Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
The Nicaraguan acting foreign minister Wednesday sent a note to
the Costa Rican Foreign Ministry voiding the agreement, which
renewed the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua refuses to permit the transit of Costa Rican
policemen with weapons on the river. The Costa Rican Foreign
Ministry said the Nicaraguan decision violates the right to free
navigation.
</P>
<P>
The conflict has exacerbated the situation and threatens to
damage relations between the two countries, which are also
experiencing tensions caused by immigration.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 600,000 Nicaraguans live in Costa Rica,
but most of them are without documents.
</P>
<P>
The Costa Rican government reiterated that it will seek ways to
avoid any confrontation with the Nicaraguan authorities.
</P>
<P>
Public Security Minister Juan Rafael Lizano said Thursday that
the changing of the guard in the four Costa Rican police posts are
being made on land, instead of using the river as done in the past.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want problems with the Nicaraguan army," said
Lizano. He also said that trade through the river continues as
usual. "The only restrictions are on public security and police
boats.
</P>
<P>
"The river is open, Nicaragua respects the free transit. the
only problem is for the uniformed ones," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
