<HEADLINE> Cuba Steps up Efforts to Cope With Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Cuban government is stepping
up efforts to reduce the impact of the drought affecting the
island nation these past months.
</P>
<P>
The government has allocated 50.5 million U.S. dollars to
alleviate the damage incurred to livestock as well as agriculture
and aquaculture, said a government news release Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Cattle are among the most frequent and hardest hit victims,
which comprise a large concentration in the eastern provinces
where the drought is the most serious.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of water facilities such as dams, small reservoirs,
and wells have dried up. As a result, drinking water for more than
300,000 head of cattle has to be transported by water tankers.
</P>
<P>
Herds of cattle have also been taken to new areas where they
can graze on green grass.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government has decided to increase the imports
of rice, milk, and vegetables to make up for agricultural losses.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the Meteorology Institute say that the total
precipitation this year was only 200 millimeters by July, just 12
percent of the annual median.
</P>
<P>
The extended heat wave, often over 35 degrees centigrade, made
the drought worse, said the institute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
