<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has offered a room in
its embassy in Lisbon, Portugal, to be used as a coordinating
office by Indonesia for the U.N.-mediated negotiation to end
long-standing East Timor issue, according to Thai Foreign Ministry
spokesman Kobsak Chutikul.
</P>
<P>
Kobsak was quoted Friday by The Nation as saying that the offer
had been approved by Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai this week after
talks with Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan who conveyed the
request from Jakarta, which do not have a diplomatic mission in
the Portuguese capital.
</P>
<P>
He said the move was part of the diplomatic effort to help
solve the East Timor problem.
</P>
<P>
Kobsak said Indonesia is to send two diplomats to Lisbon before
the end of this month, while the Portuguese government is to use
the Dutch embassy in Jakarta as its office.
</P>
<P>
he said Thailand hoped that the cooperation would facilitate
negotiations between the two countries and find a solution to the
East Timor issue.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added that the Thai embassy in Lisbon would
allocate a 15-square-meter room to Indonesian diplomats free of
charge.
</P>
<P>
The office has separate stairs and entry point.
</P>
<P>
Office staff from both countries will share public water
supplies and telephone lines. 
