<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Approves Incentives for Banks' Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines has approved a set of guidelines for fresh incentives
to encourage banks to merge or consolidate their resources, a
newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson was quoted as saying
Thursday that the new incentives for mergers and consolidation
were earlier approved by the Monetary Board, the highest
policy-making body of the central bank.
</P>
<P>
The new incentives are aimed at strengthening the banking
system by encouraging stronger players amid the difficult economic
environment triggered by the continuing Asian currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Under the guidelines, the incentives will also apply to
buy-outs or the acquisition by a bank of majority stake of up to
100 percent of another bank. Mergers mean that the two banks will
each own 50 percent of the merged bank.
</P>
<P>
The incentives include a one-year extension from compliance
with the additional 2 percent loan loss provision which banks were
earlier required by the central bank to meet within the next two
years.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Deputy Governor Alberto Reyes said merged banks
will now be given three years or an additional one year to comply
with the rule.
</P>
<P>
Other incentives include flexibility in meeting the 20-percent
cap on property loans, waiver of shareholding limit, and
restructuring of bad loans.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has been making efforts to strengthen the
country's banking system following the breakout of the Asian
financial crisis last year which has led to the closure of four
small Philippine banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Separatist Leaders Injured in Internal Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The leaders of two militant
Kosovo separatist factions were injured when they clashed with
each other while under siege by Serbian police.
</P>
<P>
The two ethnic Albanian groups, led by Naim Maljoku and Naim
Tofaj, were under siege in Junik Town, when Maljoku's force
decided to retreat into Albania and the other faction tried to
stop them.
</P>
<P>
Maljoku and Tofaj were injured in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
The Kosovo militants had retreated to the border areas between
Yugoslavia and Albania after it suffered heavy losses in an attack
by Yugoslav forces in July.
</P>
<P>
The Kosovo forces involved in the conflict were surrounded by
Serbian police in Junik. The police refrained from attacking and
called upon the militants to surrender. 
</P>
</TEXT>
