<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House to Limit Access to Report on Lewinsky Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Anticipating an impeachment
report next month from Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr, leaders
of the Judiciary Committee of the U.S. House of Representatives
are planning to restrict access to sensitive evidence by changing
a current rule that would let all 435 House members review it.
</P>
<P>
"I think we're supportive of it," Representative John Boehner,
a Republican and a member of the leadership was quoted as saying
by the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an unidentified Democratic committee official said
that party's leadership and Representative John Conyers of
Michigan, the Judiciary Committee's senior Democrat, would back
the change.
</P>
<P>
Starr is reportedly expected to focus the report solely on
evidence of perjury, obstruction of justice and witness tampering
in the Monica Lewinsky case.
</P>
<P>
But no decisions are expected to be made until after President
Bill Clinton, the last central witness, gives his account to a
grand jury via closed-circuit television on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The law under which Starr was appointed requires that such a
report be based on "substantial and credible evidence" that the
president committed an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
Any report Starr sends to Congress would form the basis for
lawmakers to decide whether to begin an impeachment inquiry that
could lead to a vote on whether to remove Clinton from office. But
many lawmakers have signaled that such proceedings probably
wouldn't start until next year.
</P>
<P>
The goal for House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, a
Republican, initially will be to confine access to the report to
members of his committee so sensitive evidence will be
safeguarded.
</P>
<P>
A resolution will be offered to the House floor to change the
current rule that gives any House member access to the report, the
report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
