<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Petroleum Industry Pursuing Profit Goals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- China's petrochemical industry
is ready to claw and scrape to reach bottom line profits this
year, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based English newspaper said that the State
Petrochemical Industry Bureau (SPIB) has drawn up a plan to boost
production and sales in the sector, which included concrete steps
to be taken by the restructured China National Petroleum Corp
(CNPC) and China Petrochemical Corp (Sinopec).
</P>
<P>
The plan forecasts that onshore crude oil output this year will
reach 143.13 million tons, 1.14 percent higher than the
previously-set target.
</P>
<P>
Processed oil output is expected to reach 159 million tons,
down 6.31 percent from previously set goals and 1.14 percent lower
than output last year.
</P>
<P>
The state petrochemical board will be in charge of supervising
production, refining, anti-smuggling and importing work of the two
petrochemical conglomerates over the next few months.
</P>
<P>
The central government, under the pressure of achieving 8
percent of overall economic growth, demanded at least 10 billion
yuan (1.2 billion US dollars) in this year's profits for the
petrochemical industry.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the two petrochemical groups reported 17.5 billion
yuan (2.108 billion US dollars) in total profits, contributing
considerably to the nation's tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said ongoing heavy flooding along the Yangtze River
and in Northeast China would affect operation of some large oil
exploration enterprises. The State petrochemical bureau has
yet to downgrade its expectations for the industry, the paper
reported.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
