<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Mahathir Says World to Enter New Millennium  with Bad Economies (1)  By Wu Dingbao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad has expressed his hope that the advent of the
21st century would lead to prosperity for the whole world, however
he anticipated that the world will enter the new millennium with
bad economies.
</P>
<P>
"First I am very hopeful that it (the advent of the 21st
century) will lead to prosperity for the whole world. I did not
believe in the so-called Asia century. I thought there will be a
world century, but now I am not so sure. I think the world will
enter the new millennium with the very bad economies," he said in
an exclusive interview with Xinhua here Thursday, with clear
reference to the current economic crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
When asked to give his views on what major changes he observes
would take place in the world power structure in the next century,
Mahathir said there will be a multiple power structure in the
world.
</P>
<P>
He said that at first the world would be dominated by "certain
world powers", but they will fail because other centers of power
will emerge including China.
</P>
<P>
"China, because of its size and because of its capacity, will
become a world power, and that will balance the other powers.
There will be multiple power structure," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir also agreed that Japan would be one of the powers in
the next century.
</P>
<P>
Asked how ASEAN (the Association of Southeast Asian Nations)
could be developed in the next century, Mahathir said ASEAN will
consolidate.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We will learn form each other and we will help each
other to develop and with that we can be very good market for
ourselves and for the rest of the world."
</P>
<P>
But Mahathir said he did not think ASEAN would be a power
center in the next century because he said "we are small
countries." "But we will be able to stabilize the region," he
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eds: More to follow hke081404 -- Interview: Mahathir says World to Enter New Millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On how fast the crisis-affected Asian economies would recover,
he said, "It is very difficult to say. For as long as the currency
traders can play around with our currencies and for as long as the
hot money can come in, there really is no stability, so we seek to
regulate the flow of capitals and ensure they are not
destructive."
</P>
<P>
"It will take time for the economies to recover for the whole
world," Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
For Asian vitalization, Mahathir said that "Firstly Asian
countries must cooperate with each other... The Asians must be
allowed to come together, at least to discuss common problems. by
that way we can be much stronger and be able to protect
ourselves."
</P>
<P>
When asked what concrete ideas he has for the international
financial system reforms, Mahathir said that firstly, currency
trading must be completely transparent and there must be a proper
place for the currency traders to do the trading and they must be
registered.
</P>
<P>
There must be regulations for example to what extent currencies
can devalue or revalue, Mahathir said, adding that also the
currency traders must give proper reasons for the devaluation.
</P>
<P>
On why Malaysia's currency and stock market continue to
fluctuate or even further plunge, Mahathir, who for long blamed
the currency traders for manipulation in currency and stock
markets, said the fluctuation in currency and stock market "has
nothing to do with the way we run the economy of this country".
</P>
<P>
"For them (currency traders), it is merely a matter of making
money for themselves. So since they can make money by devaluing
our currency and reducing the share prices they will continue to
do so.
</P>
<P>
"And they may give any kind of excuse, although these excuses
are irrelevant. What we are doing for ourselves is to minimize the
effects of the currency manipulation and share price reduction and
then enabling us to continue without having to ask for help from
IMF," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir, who repeatedly said Malaysia would depend on its own
efforts for the economic recovery, spelt out Malaysia's strong
points, "Fundamentally we are still very strong. The most
important thing for us is political stability and strong support
of the government by the people of this country, that means we can
take measures which will be fully supported."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Mahathir Says World to Enter New Millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When asked what new measures his government will take for a
quick recovery, Mahathir said, "A quick recovery is very
difficult. But we will recover through increasing our trade, and
not using the U.S. dollar, because we do not have U.S. dollars and
in any case if you buy U.S. dollars to pay for our trade, the U.S.
dollar will appreciate some more. So we have now reached
agreements with many countries to trade in our own currencies."
</P>
<P>
On how Malaysia under his leadership would be developed in the
next century, Mahathir first said he did not know how long he
would be the leader in the next century, then he said if he
continues to be in power, "we will continue to ensure growth in
order to achieve our 2020 vision. We want to become a fully
developed country by the year 2020 and if we can overcome the
currency crisis, we would be developing industrially and
particularly information technology sector in order to be a fully
developed country."
</P>
<P>
On how he envisages the Sino-Malaysian relationship in the next
century, Mahathir said, "I think it will continue to be good. it
is good now. We have very little differences and we do not
interfere in each other's internal affairs. The trade will grow
and economic cooperation will also grow. There will be more
investments in each other's country."
</P>
<P>
For the future development of the bilateral relations between
China and Malaysia, Mahathir said, "Our interest will be in the
economic field. We would like to invest more in China and we would
like China to invest here. We must increase trade between the two
countries, and we should cooperate with each other in facing the
difficult years ahead."
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said, "We are very happy that China is very stable and
I think China's stability is very important not only for China
itself but also for the region. So I hope that even though you are
democratizing, this should not result in instability for China."
</P>
<P>
Touching on the reported market fear on possible devaluation of
the Chinese currency Renminbi, Mahathir said, "I am very grateful
that China has not devalued its currency so far."
</P>
<P>
"But of course, even if you devalue a little, it would not hurt
us much because I think the difference is not so great. The
situation is now different from one year ago. One year ago, if
China had devalued its currency, it would have had very serious
consequences. But today, because other currencies are devalued too
far, even yuan devalues a bit, it will not affect us so much,"
Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his concern about whether China can sustain the
pressure of no devaluation, especially as Japan has effectively
devalued. 
</P>
</TEXT>
