<HEADLINE> Sweden and UN to Beef up Military Presence in Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Swedish government decided
Thursday to keep its United Nations peacekeeping force in
Macedonia and bolstered its military presence in the Balkan state
to 112 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. force has been in Macedonia since 1992 in an effort to
prevent Bosnia's civil war from spilling out of the borders of the
former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Due to the escalating situation in the Serb province of Kosovo,
the U.N. has also decided to beef up its military force in
Macedonia to prevent a full-blown conflict from spreading into the
country -- which has not yet been drawn into the on-again
off-again war in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. military presence has successfully contributed to
this," said Swedish Defense Minister Bjoern von Sydow. 
