<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas-Funded Businesses Growing In South China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 14 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province added 2,115 overseas-funded enterprises during the first
half of this year, involving 7.05 billion U.S. dollars of
investment, a nearly 97 percent rise from the same 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
The growing business is attributed to local promotion of
preferential policies such as taxation exemptions for overseas
investors and an improved local investment environment.
</P>
<P>
An increasing amount of overseas spendings is flowing into
local agricultural and industrial areas, while the amount into the
service sector is decreasing.
</P>
<P>
The number of new overseas-funded businesses involving
agriculture, forestry, animal husbandry, fishing and water
conservation soared 51.2 percent from the same period of 1997,
while the number in manufacturing climbed 44 percent. The number
in commerce and catering dropped 31.6 percent, and the number in
real estate fell 22.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total enterprises, 63 cost more than 10 million
U.S. dollars each and are mainly owned by overseas investors. The
enterprises focus on such businesses as manufacturing, power,
construction, storage, transportation, posts and
telecommunications and social services.
</P>
<P>
Two Sino-Japanese joint ventures producing automobiles and
motors cost more than 200 million U.S. dollars and 100 million
U.S. dollars, respectively.
</P>
<P>
More than 71.4 percent of the enterprises, or 1,539, are funded
by investors from Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
