<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin called on civilians and soldiers to
make greater efforts to fight a final triumphant battle against
the Yangtze River flooding.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, also general secretary of the Communist Party of China
Central Committee and chairman of the Central Military Commission,
arrived in Central China's Hubei Province yesterday morning amid
high temperatures to inspect the flooded areas.
</P>
<P>
-- More than 200,000 Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA)
soldiers and paramilitary forces are working on the embankments of
the Nenjiang and Songhua rivers in northeast China's Heilongjiang
Province to protect their safety.
</P>
<P>
So far, PLA soldiers have evacuated 79,000 flood-affected
people, and rescued 5,444 stranded by the flood. They have also
repaired 680 meters of breaches and reinforced 208,800 meters of
embankments, which remain safe after three flood crests.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Donation activities by members of the National Committee of
the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) for
the flooded areas should be encouraged and well organized, said Li
Ruihuan, chairman of the CPPCC National Committee, at a meeting
held yesterday on donation activities for the flood-stricken areas
along the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
-- The Ministry of Finance has allocated a total of 2.2 billion
yuan to support anti-flood campaign in the country since the
beginning of the year, especially since the flood season began.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China is willing to open up more of its fledging legal
service sector following the remarkable achievements made in the
past six years, says the Ministry of Justice.
</P>
<P>
By the end of February, the ministry had allowed 67 overseas
law firms -- 21 of them from the United States -- and 26 firms
from the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) to open
offices in the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
-- Two customs officers were convicted yesterday by the
Intermediate People's Court on charges of taking bribes and
helping illegal immigrants cross the border. One was sentenced to
death and the other was sentenced to 15 years in prison. Money and
items they received will be confiscated.  
</P>
</TEXT>
