<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Concept Of Marriage Changing In Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Shanghai, August 14 (Xinhua) -- As China opened wider to the
outside world in recent years, the people of the city of Shanghai
have kept pace and responded by changing their ideas about
marriage, according to a Civil Affairs Department study.
</P>
<P>
For one thing, people here are no longer necessarily content
with just marrying the girl or boy next door, and the number of
people marrying someone from outside Shanghai is on the
increase. In the past, few people looked for marriage partners
among the citizens of other provinces.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, some 7,200 people, or 8.17 per cent of all those
registering for marriage here, married people from other
provinces. But in 1997, the number was more than 14,000, or 16.82
percent of the marriage registrations.
</P>
<P>
The study also showed that more people are marrying foreigners,
overseas Chinese, or residents of Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan.
And, the numbers are growing: from about 800 couples a year a
decade ago to more than 3,000 couples in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Another change has been an increase in the uncontested divorce
rate. More than 11,000 couples in Shanghai got uncontested
divorces last year, compared with only 5,100 couples in 1988.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
