</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister John Howard Thursday promised 17 billion
Australian dollars (10.2 billion U.S. dollars) in giveaways,
including average tax cuts of between 40 and 50 Australian dollars
(24 to 30 U.S. dollars) a week for families and all the revenue
from a 10 percent goods and services tax to the states as part of
his election tax gamble.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald:
</P>
<P>
-- The number of long-term unemployed has jumped to the highest
level in five years, bringing to number of people who have been
unable to find work for a year or more to just over a quarter of a
million.
</P>
<P>
The Age:
</P>
<P>
-- The government has proposed a major extension of its private
health insurance incentive scheme, offering the 5 million
Australians holding private health cover a 30 percent rebate on
their premiums.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review:
</P>
<P>
-- The federal government's pre-election tax reform package has
ushered in a new era for federal-state relations with a 10 percent
goods and services tax and 13 billion Australian dollars (7.8
billion U.S. dollars) in personal income tax cuts. 
</P>
