<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lineker Joins Hoddle Critics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Former England international
Gary Lineker has joined in the criticism of Glenn Hoddle for
making public the reaction of Paul Gascoigne's reaction to being
dropped from France 98.
</P>
<P>
In his new book, Hoddle revealed that Gascoigne had gone
"berserk" after being told he would not play for England in the
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Lineker said he had never liked players being condemned by
managers in public.
</P>
<P>
"It is slightly bizarre. I don't think it serves any purpose
and cannot see what benefits you get out of the situation," he
told BBC Radio 5 Live.
</P>
<P>
"Players do not want to read about what they have perhaps said
to a manager in a confined situation or a private situation.
</P>
<P>
"I'm quite amazed that Glenn has been so frank about it, al
most too honest in many ways," said Lineker, now a BBC television
sport presenter.
</P>
<P>
"He just didn't need to mention some of the things he did.
It's not as though he is leaving the job, he is still the
incumbent. It's slightly bizarre."
</P>
<P>
But there was support for the England coach from his agent
Dennis Roach, who pointed out: "Bobby Robson did a diary
immediately after the World Cup, Terry Venables has written more
books than Enid Blyton." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Local Hero Holm Wins Stage in Tour of Denmark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Local hero Brian Holm headed
countryman Frank Hoy to win the third leg of the Tour of Denmark
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the Danes had captured two consecutive stage victories
in a race where a native hadn't won in two years.
</P>
<P>
Holm clocked 5 hours 42 seconds to complete the 215 kilometers
from Odder to Svendborg, the race's second longest leg.
</P>
<P>
Holm broke away with Hoy in the last 60 kilometers and stayed
together to cross the finishing line almost simultaneously by
holding each other's hands up.
</P>
<P>
Both Holm and Hoy were more than four minutes ahead of the
pack, but neither had increased his spot into the top 10 in the
overall standings wherein Belgian Marc Streel still led Dane Bo
Hamburger by 41 seconds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
