<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Dollar Falls Below 50 U.S. Cent Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand share market
slumped to the three and a half years low and the local dollar
fell through 50 U.S. cents for the second time in 12 years
Thursday as local financial markets grappled with the implications
of a breakup of the governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
The current coalition government is formed by the New Zealand
National Party with Prime Minister Jenny Shipley as its leader and
the New Zealand First with Deputy Prime Minister Winston Peters as
its leader.
</P>
<P>
The latest political turmoil was triggered by Peters' walkout
of a special cabinet meeting Wednesday night as a decision was
about to be taken to sell the government's shareholding in the
Wellington International Airport.
</P>
<P>
The walkout was followed by an exchange of accusation of each
other at the local TV station, pulling the governing coalition
apart.
</P>
<P>
According to The Dominion, a Wellington-based newspaper, the NZ
dollar, which fell a third of a U.S. cent when news of the
coalition chaos hit, drifted lower Thursday and eventually broke
through the U.S. 50 cents barrier to close at 49.95 cents.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand share market has shed four percent in two days,
wiping 1.8 billion NZ dollars (some 900 million U.S. dollars) off
its value, and closed Thursday at its lowest since January 1995.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the political instability caused by Peters'
walking out on the cabinet came on top of a host of negative
global factors, not least the Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
Local foreign exchange dealers said that the NZ dollar had
fared relatively well in light of the domestic political ructions.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand economists warned of gloomy treasury fiscal
forecast. In the government budget, the Treasury forecast GDP
growth of 2.7 percent and a government surplus of 1.3 billion NZ
dollars (about 650 million U.S. dollars) for the year to March
1999.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion quoted Bankers Trust chief economist David Plank
as saying that there is the possibility that in the year to next
March, economic growth and the government's operating balance
could be negative.
</P>
<P>
"They'll probably have zero to negative growth in the year to
March 1999, and a fiscal surplus below 500 million NZ dollars
(about 250 million U.S. dollars), which could easily turn out to
be negative," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tony Alexander, chief economist of the Bank of New Zealand,
said that previous predictions of an upturn in the second half of
this year were "extremely optimistic". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
