<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Decides to Extend Mandate of MONUA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations on Thursday decided to extend the mandate of
the United Nations Observer Mission (MONUA) in Angola for a
further period of one month until September 15, 1998.
</P>
<P>
In its resolution unanimously adopted, the Security Council
welcome the decision by the UN Secretary-General to dispatch a
Special Envoy to assess the situation in Angola and advise on a
possible course of action.
</P>
<P>
The Council called on the Government of Unity and National
Reconciliation of Angola and in particular the National Union for
the Total Independence for Angola (UNITA) in the strongest terms
to refrain from any steps which could further exacerberate the
present situation.
</P>
<P>
The Council demanded that UNITA comply immediately and without
conditions with its obligations under the Lusaka Protocol and with
relevant Security Council resolutions, in particular the complete
demilitarization of its forces and full cooperation in the
immediate and unconditional extension of State administration
throughout the national territory, in order to prevent a further
deterioration of the political and security situation.
</P>
<P>
The Council also demanded that UNITA cease its reoccupation of
localities where State Administration was established and stop
attacks by its members on civilians, including police, and the
United Nations and international personnel.
</P>
<P>
The Council demanded the Government of Angola and in particular
UNITA cooperate fully with MONUA in providing full access for its
verification activities and guarantee unconditionally the safety
and freedom of movement of all United Nations and international
personnel, including those providing humanitarian assistance.
</P>
<P>
It expressed its firm belief that a meeting in Angola between
the President of Angola and the leader of UNITA could provide
momentum to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Council welcomed the appointment of a new Special
Representative to Angola, and urged both sides to cooperate fully
with him in promoting peace ans national reconciliation.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
