<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Banks under Pressure to Settle Nazi Gold Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Two German major banks came under
increasing pressure Thursday to settle a 18-billion-U.S. dollar
compensation claim made by Holocaust victims after a compensation
deal was reached with leading Swiss banks on the same day.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement reached in New York, two biggest Swiss bank,
Credit Suisse and UBS, agreed to pay 1.25 billion dollars to
settle the dispute over lost assets deposited by Holocaust victims
in Switzerland during World War II.
</P>
<P>
Lawyers representing Holocaust victims and their heirs made
clear Thursday after the deal that they would now concentrate on
similar lawsuits against German banks.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement in New York has not settle the whole issue.
Things are now starting to get going," said lawyer Michael Witti
in the southern German city of Munich.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the German news agency DPA, leader of the
Jewish community in Germany, Ignatz Bubis, also hailed the
agreement reached in New York and called for a quick resolution of
the Nazi gold dispute concerning German banks.
</P>
<P>
At issue is a class-action suit launched by Holocaust survivors
in June in New York charging that the two biggest German banks,
the Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank, had profited from Holocaust
victims' personal assets like gold teeth fillings, gold jewellery
and coins seized by German Nazis during World War II.
</P>
<P>
The Holocaust survivors demanded 18 billion U.S. dollars in
compensation from the two German banks.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the latest development on Thursday, the Deutsche
Bank said the legal action against the Swiss banks was not
comparable with that concerning the two German banks.
</P>
<P>
A Dresdner Bank spokesman also noted that a New York court had
still to decide whether it would finally accept the lawsuit
against the German banks.
</P>
<P>
Both German banks have denied any wrongdoings concerning the
Nazi gold dispute, arguing that the gold received by them from
Nazi Germany's central bank had been delivered in the form of
bullions so that its origin was not known. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Develop "Very Long Carbon Nanotubes" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- A team of Chinese researchers
announced Thursday in Nature, the international science journal,
that they have made "very long carbon nanotubes" which are up to 2
millimetre.
</P>
<P>
The same method, which involved passing acetylene in nitrogen
over an iron-silica catalyst, could produce even longer nanotubes,
said the researchers from the Institute of Physics of the Chinese
Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The scientists said that very long nanotubes may be useful in
the probe tips of scanning tunnelling microscopes, field emission
materials and nanotube-reinforced materials.
</P>
<P>
Nanotubes are strands of carbon molecules with unusual
properties. But until now, there has been no way of produce
nanotubes that are more than a fraction of a millimetre long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
