<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges Russia to Restore Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The United States urged
Russia on Thursday to take immediate actions to restore confidence
and stability in its economy, expressing its confidence in the
Russian government.
</P>
<P>
"It is critical that the Russian government act quickly to
restore confidence in their economy, and that is something we have
communicated with Russian officials," White House spokesman Mike
McCurry told a regular news briefing.
</P>
<P>
"The international community has a big stake in seeing that
Russia gets their economy moving in the right direction," said
McCurry.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. have confidence in the Russian leaders. "The
United States and others in the world community have a great deal
of confidence in the reform-minded leaders of the Russian
government," he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the U.S. believes that "if everyone works
together, it can be in the best interest not only of the people of
Russia, but the people of the world economy."
</P>
<P>
He confirmed reports about backing for Russia by the Group of
Seven (G-7) industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
"I would not be surprised if the G7 remains fully engaged in
monitoring both the developments in Russia and in Asia generally,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he declined to comment on whether Russia should
devalue the ruble currency or if a currency board, pegging the
ruble to the dollar, would be appropriate.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton is to meet Russian President Boris
Yeltsin early next month. High on the agenda will be Russia's
economic difficulties and arms control.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Yeltsin will discuss "economic reform, the health
and vibrancy of the Russian economy," said McCurry.
</P>
<P>
"We obviously will discuss the need for ratifying and moving
ahead with START II, but it's always been foreseen that there is
an arms-control agenda that moves out beyond START II that
includes the kinds of outlines that...could conceivably lead to a
START III agreement," he added.
</P>
<P>
The United States was a key player in drawing up a 22.5 billion
U.S. dollars international rescue package for Russia last month
and Treasury Undersecretary David Lipton, a senior Treasury
official, flew to Moscow this week for top-level talks.
</P>
<P>
Lipton had met Russian Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko and
officials from the finance ministry and the central bank to
communicate "the sense of urgency we have about the need to
restore both confidence and stability in the Russian economy,"
said McCurry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
