<HEADLINE> Myanmar Says No Reason for Rushed Visit by U.N. Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has said its
dialogue with the U.N. Secretary-General could continue, while
rejecting a proposed visit by a U.N. envoy to look into the
current situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General Kofi Annan wrote last week to the Myanmar
leader Gen. Than Shwe, proposing to send a special emissary to
Myanmar towards the end of the week for discussions on the current
developments, U.N. spokesman Juan Carlos Brandt told reporters
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said: "Given the special nature of the visit, the
Secretary-General has requested that Ambassador Razali Ismail (of
Malaysia), President of the 51st General Assembly, be his special
emissary at this particular time.
</P>
<P>
"The response from the Prime Minister (Gen. Than Shwe) was
polite but he stated that there was no reason for such a rushed
visit and that the dialogue that the Secretary-General and the
Government of Myanmar had maintained since 1994 could continue
when the Foreign Minister of Myanmar is in New York next month for
the General Assembly's general debate.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General is disappointed by the response."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman was replying to questions about the U.N. attitude
towards the current situation in Myanmar regarding the differences
between the government and the opposition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
