<HEADLINE> U.S. Sends Ship for Possible Evacuation from Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Thursday that it had sent a helicopter-carrying ship with 1,200
Marines toward the Democratic Republic of the Congo in case it is
needed to evacuate U.S. citizens from the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon told reporters that the USS
Saipan, an amphibious assault ship, left the French Mediterranean
port of Marseilles on Wednesday morning and would arrive off the
coast of the country.
</P>
<P>
"No decision has been made to evacuate Americans," Bacon said.
"All we are doing is positioning ourselves should such a decision
be made by the State Department."
</P>
<P>
Bacon said there were about 250 Americans in the country, where
rebels are advancing on the capital, Kinshasa, vowing to overthrow
President Laurent Kabila's government.
</P>
<P>
The likely evacuation route would be across the river from
Kinshasa to Brazzaville, Congo, where evacuees could be taken by
helicopter to Libreville, Gabon, or to ships standing offshore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
