<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cook Unveils Measures on Curbing EC Powers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook Thursday put forward a range of measures designed to curb the
powers of the European Commission (EC).
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an interview with the New Statesman magazine
published Thursday, Cook said that a new European Union (EU) code
should be drawn up to tighten the rules of subsidiarity, the
principle which says some decisions should not be taken
automatically by Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Cook made it clear that such a code could be regarded as "a
working guide to Europe and to the nation state." Such a code
could set out the responsibilities of Europe and those of
individual member states, he added.
</P>
<P>
Cook argued that EU headquarters should adopt more general
European standards of practice rather than impose strict
directives on its members.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment it is a matter of imposed legislation. Much
better if we agree standards at European level, but recognize that
sometimes member states come up with a technical way to meet these
standards which are more appropriate for them," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the British foreign secretary proposed to
establish a new European Forum which would allow for greater
contact between national governments across the 15-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment there is not an adequate basis for
representation fro the national parliaments to come together to
discuss Europe. We must develop some way to link in the
parliaments of the member states," he added.
</P>
<P>
A British Foreign Office official told reporters that Britain
is expected to table these proposals at the special EU summit due
to be held in Vienna, Austria, in October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
