<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Diplomats Safe: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Foreign Ministry
spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi stated on Thursday that the missing
Iranian diplomats in Afghanistan are sound and safe.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the evening daily Kayhan, Mohammadi said
that the Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz assured Iran the
missing Iranian diplomats are sound and safe and would be
transferred from Bamian, northern Afghanistan to Islamabad,
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said that the Iranian diplomats would be handed over
to the Iranian officials in Pakistan in the near future.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman did not mention how the Iranian
diplomats reached Bamian.
</P>
<P>
Aziz announced on Wednesday that the missing Iranian diplomats
left Mazar-e-Sharif along with the forces of the Afghan opposition
Northern Alliance to Bamian. He informed his Iranian counterpart
Kamal Kharrazi of the issue Thursday morning when Kharrazi was in
Azerbaijan for a visit.
</P>
<P>
Iran earlier announced that the Afghan fundamentalist Taliban
forces captured 11 Iranian diplomats and a correspondent of the
official news agency IRNA residing in Mazar-e-Sharif on Saturday
when they took control of the city.
</P>
<P>
However, the Taliban stated that they did not hold any Iranian
diplomats and the Iranian consulate general in Mazar-e-Sharif had
been evacuated when their forces reached.
</P>
<P>
Tehran argued available evidence proved that the Iranian
diplomats and reporter were in the hands of the Taliban and were
transferred to Qandahar, the group's headquarters in southern
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Iran has condemned the Taliban for violating international
laws and norms and held Pakistan, the Taliban's main supporter,
responsible for the safety and release of the Iranian diplomats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
