<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disaster Management Training Necessary: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Disaster management courses are
needed to avoid bomb attacks similar to the ones which claimed
more than 200 lives in Kenya and Tanzania last Friday, a Zimbabwe
National Army (ZNA) administrative officer said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Brigadier Sibusiso Moyo told 30 officers, who completed a
month-long disaster management course, that the lack of skills had
resulted in some people remaining buried in the debris in Kenya,
the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A huge blast which rippled through Kenya Capital Nairobi
Friday was followed soon after by another in the Tanzanian
capital Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
A total of 247 people were killed while more than 4,000 were
injured in Nairobi alone.
</P>
<P>
"Disasters come without warning and often require speedy action
to tackle," said Moyo.
</P>
<P>
"That is why we are saying it is important that we put such a
plan in place," he added.
</P>
<P>
The course was designed to equip armymen with skills to handle
drought, famine and civil unrest disasters, he said.
</P>
<P>
The training, dubbed the Flintlock Two Operations, is part of the
annual joint cooperation between the U.S. army and ZNA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Hopeful to Overcome Temporary Economic Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 13 (Xinhua) -- A senior government official
has expressed the confidence that with a three-pronged strategy,
the Pakistani government will overcome the current provisional
economic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Hafiz Pasha, adviser to the prime minister on finance and
economic affairs, said during an interview Thursday evening with
the Pakistan TV that the government has first of all announced a
comprehensive package of measures aimed at boosting exports,
restricting imports and increasing the inflow of remittances
particularly through banking channels.
</P>
<P>
Domestically, Pasha said, the government is trying to
concentrate on improving the balance of payments position.
</P>
<P>
Beyond that, the government has also been working to get
support from the Islamic world and it has already been able to put
into place an oil facility with the help of the Saudi government
and has also received medium-term assistance from the Kuwaiti
government.
</P>
<P>
Pasha said that currently the government is working with the
Islamic Development Bank on enhanced trade-financing and
establishment of the Pakistan Fund.
</P>
<P>
According to Pasha, Pakistan has also started a process of
dialogue with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and other
international institutions after the withdrawal of objections by
the United States and some other countries.
</P>
<P>
"The IMF has come back and resumed its dialogue with us and we
are trying to put together a program with the support of the fund
also," Pasha added.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that with these three measures combined,
Pakistan will be able to overcome the temporary difficulties
resulting from the sanctions imposed on it by some countries after
its nuclear tests in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
