<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kiriyenko Confident in Overcoming Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko Thursday said there have been no financial causes for
the current crisis on the Russian financial market and it has been
caused by psychological reasons.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a briefing in the government building, Kiriyenko
said the Central Bank's currency reserve is larger now than it was
in July, when the situation was more complicated and the budget
for August is well-balanced.
</P>
<P>
The premier said that the government will respond to the panic
with strict implementation of the stabilization program by the
government.
</P>
<P>
In Kiriyenko's opinion, the current panic on the Russian market
has been caused by external factors, first of all by a fall of
world oil prices and a crisis on the Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
He promised that back arrears for July will be paid in August
and that wages for the current month will be fully paid. The debt
will also be serviced adequately, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the Interfax news agency, Russian blue chip stocks
dived 15-25 percent in the first two hours of trading Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Trading was suspended on the RTS, the Moscow Interbank Currency
Exchange, and the Moscow Stock Exchange on recommendations by the
Federal Securities Commission.
</P>
<P>
Head of investment at General Securities Mechislav Sheshelovsky
said the Federal Securityies Commission's orders to halt trading
are on target.
</P>
<P>
The crisis on the interbank loan market triggered foreign
investors to close limits for their Russian partners.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank has imposed limitations on currency volumes
brought by traders, prohibiting banks to acquire currency in
excess of the clients' bids and introducing a "supply against
payment" principle in interbank operations.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax quoted Central Bank spokesman Irina Yasina as
saying that beginning Thursday, the Central Bank will deal with
commercial banks on the interbank market on the basis of the
"supply against payment" principle.
</P>
<P>
Until now the Central Bank has dealt with banks without
depositing rubles, thus assuming the risk of non-supplies. The
introduction of a new procedure is expected to remove this risk,
Yasina said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
