<HEADLINE> Angolan Peace Process Makes No Headway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Angolan peace talks continued
Thursday with no breakthrough made on some key issues left
unsettled since the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government and the rebel National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) found their views quite
apart from each other in such issues like the full disarmament of
UNITA, the re-establishement of government institutions in four
major cities in central Angola, and the re-location of UNITA
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
UNITA suggested days ago to postpone to October the date of
the re-establishment of government institutions in four cities of
Bailundo, Andulo, Nharea and Mungo.
</P>
<P>
The government warned, however, that if UNITA fails to disarm
its army, refuses to re-establish government institutions in the
four cities and move its headquarters to Luanda by the end of the
month, the government would drive UNITA representatives out of
the reconciliation government.
</P>
<P>
The peace conference, resumed on August 7 under the mediation
of UN special envoy Lakhdar Brahimi, was held when the country's
peace process fell in one of the worst crises in four years.
</P>
