<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Minister of State
responsible for state enterprises and indigenization, Cephas
Msipa Thursday has challenged youths to take the lead in
employment creation and contribute towards alleviating poverty.
</P>
<P>
He said the older generation had fought for political freedom
and the struggle to economically empower the marginalized
indigenous people should now be led by youths.
</P>
<P>
He was opening a one-day workshop organized by the Zimbabwe
Youth in Business (ZYB) to discuss the role of youths in the
indigenization of the economy, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The government, he said, was confident that youths could play
a greater role in the indigenization of the economy.
</P>
<P>
"As we hand over the baton to you, we expect you to accept
your full responsibility in participating in the economic
development of our country with zeal, vigor, dignity and
patriotism," Msipa said.
</P>
<P>
President of the ZYB Bernard Jiro said it was time the
government seriously considered involving youths in matters of
national policy, particularly economic issues.
</P>
<P>
He said his organization supported the government's land
redistribution program and urged the state to give land to graduates
from the country's agriculture colleges.
</P>
<P>
The workshop was attended by about 50 participants from banks,
government, non-governmental organizations and black economic
empowerment lobby groups.  
