<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Volatile after Russian Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- A crash on the Russian stock
market, which was fueled by a call of international financier
George Soros for a devaluation of the rouble, added to the gloom
in European markets, resulting in highly volatile trade Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 Index in London slumped to 5,399.5, its lowest
finish since late January, losing 62.7 points or 1.15 percent, as
traders bailed out of key stocks.
</P>
<P>
The plunge initially came after an appalling session in Hong
Kong, but losses increased after news of trading being temporarily
halted on the Russian market in the wake of a 15 percent plunge.
</P>
<P>
A better-than-expected performance on Wall Street pulled
European markets out of their slump, with the Dow Industrials down
about 0.3 percent as European bourses closed.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, shares staged a recovery from session lows as the
Dow recorded a mixed start, with the Xetra Dax closing 31.91
points or 0.59 percent lower at 5355.03. Despite an afternoon
rally, traders said the worsening situation in Russia continued to
prompt investors to swap into bond markets.
</P>
<P>
French shares in Paris rallied by close as Wall Street managed
to hold off a big reversal on its opening. The CAC-40 closed 5.99
points or 0.15 percent higher on the day at 3951.69. However,
traders said sentiment was clouded by fears of currency
devaluation in Asia and Russian market meltdown.
</P>
<P>
Norwegian stocks were the worst performing in Europe, falling
1.77 percent to 14-month lows amid rising domestic interest rates
and worries about oil prices.
</P>
<P>
However, reports of a special meeting of the Group of Seven
industrialized nations to discuss the Russian financial crisis
brought an added degree of nervousness to the mix, according to
market analysts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
