<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Attains 95 Percent of Revenue Target in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Finance Minister
Sufian Ahmed announced Thursday that his government has collected
6.7 billion Birr (about 957 million U.S. Dollars) from tax and
non-tax revenues in 1997/98 budget year, 95 percent of the
original target of seven billion Birr (about one billion U.S.
Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Such performance is quite satisfactory at a time when
agriculture, the sector which the country's economy is dependent
upon, has been affected by the El-Nino weather phenomenon, the
Ethiopian News Agency quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia's 1997/98 budget year ended on July 7, 1998. The
nation harvested 8.78 million tons of crop in 1997/98, a 16
percent decrease compared with that in 1996/97.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that efforts were also made to minimize
regular expense with a view to balancing government revenue and
expenditure.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian government has managed to save money for capital
expenses, development and investment, Ahmed said, adding that the
tendency of depending on foreign aid and loan to cover capital
and recurrent budget has declined.
</P>
<P>
Yet, budget deficit is expected and the deficit could be
offset through loans and aids, the minister was quoted by the
report as saying. 
</P>
