<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus' Water Reserves Decrease Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' water reserves in dams
are rapidly decreasing with fears that many of them will be empty
by the end of the year, if there is no rainfall.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by Water Development Department
Thursday, a total of 26,900,000 cubic meters of water remain in
the island's dams, or just 10 percent of their total capacity.
</P>
<P>
The quantity of water in the dams for last year's
corresponding period was 44,100,000 cubic meters of water,
representing 16.4 percent of the total capacity.
</P>
<P>
Acting Director of Water Development Department, Christos
Markoulis, said Thursday, however, that the recent heatwave which
plagued Cyprus, did not actually contribute to the low-level water
reserves.
</P>
<P>
He said the heatwave did not last long therefore it did not
result in great evaporation of the water reserves.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Minister of Agriculture, Natural Resources and
Environment, Costas Themistocleous, announced a number of measures
to tackle the water shortage, including the introduction of mobile
desalination plants.
</P>
<P>
He said 1999 would be one of the most difficult years because
water supplies would run out completely by the end of this year
and the second desalination plant would not be ready.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has one desalination plant in Dhekelia on the
southeastern coast. A second one is expected to be completed
after the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, the last time Cyprus dams had reached
tragic levels was during the year 1990-1991.
</P>
<P>
However, heavy rainfall during December 1991 virtually saved
the island after a flow of 40 million cubic meters of water into
the dams. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980814.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-14 </DATE_TIME>
