<HEADLINE> Britain Withdraws From Military Satellite Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Britain would pull out of a
tri-national military project to develop a new generation of
satellite, according to a report in Thurday's Financial Times
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Britain signed up to the joint military venture with France and
Germany last December, hailing it as a flagship example of how
European Union member states could work together on big defense
projects.
</P>
<P>
However, British Minister of State for Defense Procurement Lord
Gilbert said Wednesday that Britain would withdraw from the
project because it was incapable of delivering a satellite in time
for Britiain's deadline of about 2005.
</P>
<P>
Lord Gilbert noted that Britain would now concentrate on "a
national solution" to its military satellite needs following its
decision to quit the 1.62-billion-dollar Trimilsatcom project.
</P>
<P>
"We remain strong supporters of collaboration in the field of
equipment procurement and a decision not to pursue a major program
like this is not taken lightly," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Britain's French and German counterparts reacted
with anger, terming Britain's actions as "without precedent." The
two countries are expected to hold talks to decide whether to
proceed with a bilateral venture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
