<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan and Israel will soon pick up the once-stalled
discussions on an Israeli intention to build an 80 million dollars
worth of bromine plant in the kingdom, the semi-official Jordan
Times Thursday quoted Roey Gilad, spokesman of the Israeli Embassy
in Jordan, as saying.
</P>
<P>
In May this year, Jordan dropped out of the negotiations with
Israel's Dead Sea Bromine (DSB) Group and reached an accord with a
United States company to establish such a plant.
</P>
<P>
The DSB Group said that the Jordanian-U.S. project was
"economically illogical" and intended to snatch back the contract
or get the permission to establish another bromine plant in
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Israel has agreed to "greatly" reduce customs duties
on Jordanian commodities such as air-conditioning units,
televisions and ceramics to be exported to Israel and the West
Bank areas, Jordan Times reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made during a meeting between Jordanian
Minister of Trade, Commerce and Supply Hani Mulqi and his Israeli
counterpart Natan Sharansky Wednesday in Tel Aviv, the report said.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon has signed a contract worth 8.2 million
U.S. dollars with a Canadian company to computerize and upgrade
the country's land registration system.
</P>
<P>
The deal with the Canadian firm CRC Sogema is part of the
ongoing efforts to modernize Lebanon's administration which was
wrecked during the 1975-1990 civil war and improve its
performance, the Daily Star newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that the deal will make possible the
automatic registration of property sales and allow foreigners to
verify the legality of their property purchases within minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
