<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat: Peace Process in Deep Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat said Thursday that the peace process is in deep crisis due
to Israel's refusal to implement the signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the remarks in Gaza city upon his return from South
Africa, the Voice of Palestine reported.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said no progress has been made so far in the
Palestinian-Israeli talks, which were resumed last month, because
of Israel's rejection to all initiatives to save the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat renewed his call for an urgent Arab summit to face the
hazards caused by Israel's settlement expansionist policies.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader has been for months pressing for an Arab
summit, which has not been materialized due to the differences
among Arab nations over the agenda, venue and timing.
</P>
<P>
During his speech, Arafat also urged the convention of an
international conference initiated by France and Egypt to seek
ways to save the long-stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb Erekat, who accompanied
Arafat on the visit to South Africa, said that the Palestinian
side would not accept any Israeli idea which is outside of the
framework of the signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
No contacts were arranged in the past few days on whether to
continue the direct talks on Israel's troop redeployment in the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
At the request of the U.S., the leading broker in the Mideast
peace process, the Palestinians and Israelis resumed direct talks
on July 19 to discuss the U.S. initiative on the Israeli pullback.
</P>
<P>
Little progress has been made so far because Israel attempted
to revise the U.S. plan which calls for a 13.1 percent Israeli
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Israel proposed to hand back 10 percent of the West Bank while
keeping the other 3 percent as "nature reserve", in which the
Palestinians are not allowed to build houses.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Arafat's three-day visit to South Africa, Erekat
said the Palestinian diplomatic efforts are intended to let the
international community know Israel's intransigence and to seek
international help in reactivating the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
