<HEADLINE> Russia Launches Soyuz TM-28 Spacecraft to Mir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Soyuz TM-28
spacecraft was launched to the Mir space station from Baikonur at
13:43 Moscow time Thursday, according to the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
The crew comprises commander Gennady Padalka, flight engineer
Sergei Avdeyev and state advisor, ex-secretary of the Defense
Council and presidential aide Yuri Baturin.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov came to Baikonur to see off
the cosmonauts.
</P>
<P>
In the 26th expedition Baturin will spend 10 days on Mir. He
will perform over 20 technical, bio-chemical, geo-physical,
biological and bio-medical experiments, returning to Earth on
August 25.
</P>
<P>
Padalka and Avdeyev will spend 201 days on Mir. They will carry
out a series of scientific experiments and prepare equipment for
research under Russian-French and Russian-Slovak programs.
</P>
<P>
The three astronauts will also make two walks in the space.
</P>
<P>
Soyuz TM-28 is to dock with Mir on August 15 at 2:48 p.m.
Moscow time, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
