<HEADLINE> Lott Urges Clinton to Cooperate on Health Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Senate Republican Leader
Trent Lott has said the Senate may not consider health care
quality legislation this year unless President Bill Clinton
encourages cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"Your veto threat only makes our job harder," Lott said in a
letter to the White House released by the Republican leader's
office Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a gathering Monday in Louisville, Kentucky, Clinton
said that he will veto Republican legislation to regulate health
plans, because it offers less security from abuses than his
administration's "patient's bill of rights."
</P>
<P>
The president also told Americans to consider the partisan
disagreement over health care when they vote in congressional
elections this fall.
</P>
<P>
Lott responded with a letter dated Tuesday, saying "we believe
the American people want a change in law, not a campaign issue."
</P>
<P>
Lott asked for a public statement from Clinton "that indicates
your willingness to work with us, not against us."
</P>
<P>
"Without your cooperation, we fear that we may not be able to
consider health care quality legislation this fall," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a followup letter Thursday, Senate Minority Leader Tom
Daschle said Senate Democrats will support Clinton in a veto
fight.
</P>
<P>
"If patients' rights are not adequately protected, or if 113
million Americans are excluded from the protections, Congress will
have no right to claim that it has passed meaningful HMO (Health
Maintenance Organization) reform," Daschle wrote. "My Democratic
colleagues and I stand firmly behind your decision to veto such
legislation if it reaches your desk."
</P>
<P>
The House has passed health care legislation crafted by
Republican leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
