<HEADLINE> Jordan Denies Urging Palestinians to Accept </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Jordanian government Thursday
denied it had urged the Palestinians to accept an Israeli proposal
of troops withdrawal from West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The denial came in a government statement issued in response to
a non-official Al Quds newspaper report which said Jordan had
advised the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) to accept the
Israeli offer.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks were resumed three weeks
ago, the first time in 16 months, but only to come to a stalemate
again.
</P>
<P>
The talks centered on a peace proposal put forward by the
United States, which calls for Israel to evacuate from 13.1
percent of the occupied Palestinian lands.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have already accepted the proposal. Israel
rejected it and suggested instead a 10 percent handover of the
West Bank together with limited Palestinian rule over a further 3
percent, which was designed as a "nature reserve."
</P>
<P>
Turning down Al Quds' report as baseless, the statement said it
did not conform with Jordan's stand on the PNA, which is in firm
support of the Palestinians' pursuit to restore their national
rights on their own soil.
</P>
<P>
"We have explained our position on this issue on many
occasions and at all levels and our position is fully identical
with that of the Palestinian brothers," it added.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has been keeping a close watch on the developments of
the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, for its national security
interests are at stake.
</P>
<P>
Jordan supports the Palestinians to establish an independent
state with its capital in Jerusalem, while it sticks to a policy
of normalizing ties with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is now Israel's closest ally in the Arab world. It is
one of the two Arab countries that have singed peace treaty with
Israel. The other is Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
