<HEADLINE> Security Council Concerned Over Developments in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations Thursday expressed its grave concern over the
continuing escalation of fighting in Afghanistan caused by the
Taleban forces' offensive in the northern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the council was briefed on the
latest developments in Afghanistan, current Security Council
President and Slovenia's Ambassador to the United Nations Danilo
Turk said the council members also expressed their concern over
the grave humanitarian crisis in the country which has been
deepened further as a result of the recent offensive by the
Taleban.
</P>
<P>
The council called on all parties concerned in the country to
respect the humanitarian law and human rights as well as the
access of international humanitarian aid to the people in need.
</P>
<P>
The council members condemned the complete disregard by the
Taleban towards the will of the international community and in
particular the presidential statement by the Security Council on
August 6 which remanded an urgent and unconditional cease-fire
leading to the final ending of the hostilities.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council was deeply concerned at the reports of the
capture by the Taleban of the consul general of Iran and called it
a violation of international law, and urged the immediate release
of the diplomat.
</P>
<P>
The council was deeply concerned over the persistent reports of
outside military involvement in the country and called on all
states concerned to refrain from any outside interference in the
internal affairs of Afghanistan, including the involvement of
military personnel.
</P>
<P>
The council reiterated its position that there is no military
solution to the Afghan conflict and demanded an end to bloodshed
and resumption of peaceful dialogue under the auspices of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The military forces Taleban last month launched offensives in
the northern part of the country. Reports say the Taleban has
captured key provinces in the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
