<HEADLINE> Security Council Condemns Violence, Human Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations Thursday strongly condemned the violence and
human right abuse against the Congolese citizens.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a briefing on the situation in the
Democratic Republic of the Congo, current Security Council
President and Slovenia's Ambassador to the United Nations Danilo
Turk said the council urged all parties concerned to respect human
rights norms and international humanitarian law.
</P>
<P>
The council was deeply disturbed by the reports of ethnic
persecution and called for immediate cessation, and called on all
parties to stop recruiting child soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The council called on all states in the region to respect the
sovereignty and territorial integrity of the Democratic Republic
of the Congo and of all states in the region.
</P>
<P>
It called upon the government of the Democratic Republic of the
Congo to permit immediate access of international aid workers to
monitor and address the needs of the victims of the violence.
</P>
<P>
The council called for an end to the hostilities and the
cessation of the external involvement as well as the need to
protect all ethnic groups and all individuals including refugees.
</P>
<P>
The council expressed its firm support for the initiatives by
the states in the region and the Organization of African Union
aimed to mediate and solve the conflict by peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
An uprising by rebel forces broke out on August 2 in the
capital of the Congo. Fighting between the government forces and
the rebels is still going on in the eastern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
Kabila's government has accused Rwanda and Uganda of playing
part in the fighting which was denied by the two countries.
</P>
