<HEADLINE> Mozambican Supreme Court Declares Elections as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Supreme Court, as
the constitutional court of Mozambique, Thursday declared as
valid the municipal elections held on June 30 in 33 cities and
towns around the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the election law of Mozambique, the Supreme Court
plays the role of the constitutional court if the later is
absent.
</P>
<P>
Reading the verdict, President of the Supreme Court Mario
Mangaze pointed out that the judges agreed to the validity of the
elections, overruling the opposition concerns about the official
results.
</P>
<P>
Mangaze said that the votes in the 33 electoral zones had all
been rightfully checked and correctly counted.
</P>
<P>
The president noted that the supreme court had not found any
rigging in the process.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the high rate of abstention from voting, Mangaze
said that it had nothing to do with the validity of the election
results.
</P>
<P>
Five of the seven judges of the Mozambican Supreme Court have
signed on the verdict.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that among the 1.965 million voters in the 33
cities and towns, 1.678 million abstained.
</P>
<P>
The largest opposition party Mozambican National Resistance
(Renamo) and other 15 opposition parties boycotted the local
elections.
</P>
<P>
They claimed that the results of the voting were invalid on
the ground that the abstention rate mounted up to 85.42 percent.
</P>
<P>
Renamo President Afonso Dhlakama said recently that the
supreme court would lose the trust of the people if it declared
the elections valid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
