<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second Bomb Threat at Swazi U.S. Embassy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The United States Embassy
in Swaziland was working aggressively on a method to trace hoax
bomb threats, after it received the second threat Thursday in
three days.
</P>
<P>
An anonymous caller telephoned the embassy in Mbabane at about
2:00 p.m. (12:00 GMT) and told a secretary that a bomb had been
planted in the building and was due to go off at any time.
</P>
<P>
The seven-story Swazi Central Bank building, in which the U.S.
mission occupies the top floor office, was immediately evacuated.
</P>
<P>
Police sealed off all access roads and diverted traffic.
</P>
<P>
Bomb disposal experts were called to the building again and
they used sniffer dogs to search all seven floors and the
adjoining car parks but no bomb was discovered.
</P>
<P>
The embassy received a similar bomb threat from an anonymous
caller Tuesday morning, causing a similar security operation by
police.
</P>
<P>
The embassy spokesman Thursday appeared unconcerned about the
incident, which he said was just another hoax by "silly callers"
exploiting the present situation.
</P>
<P>
He said the embassy was working aggressively on a method by
which such callers could be immediately traced and apprehended.
</P>
<P>
Last week massive bomb blasts at the U.S. embassies in Kenya
and Tanzania killed more than 200 people and injured over 5,000.
Twelve Americans were among the dead in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador to Swaziland Alan MacKee said Tuesday that
hoax bomb threats were to be expected in the wake of these
bombings, but all threats had to be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
MacKee said security had been stepped up at the Mbabane
embassy, its staff houses and the embassy's separate cultural
center and library.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that there was hoax bomb threat in the Hilton
Hotel in Kenyan capital Nairobi Thursday, but no explosion
occurred. 
</P>
</TEXT>
