<HEADLINE> FBI to Bring Bombing Evidence Back to Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The first pieces of evidence
from last week's twin bombings in Kenya and Tanzania will be
brought to Washington at the weekend for forensic testing, an FBI
official said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We are at the point of organizing a cargo flight... the first
evidence will arrive at the weekend," said FBI laboratory director
Donald Kerr. He added that the first planeloads would consist of
smaller pieces of wreckage and other evidence.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the United States had received
permission from authorities i Nairobi and Dar es Salaam to send
evidence back to Washington where it would undergo sophisticated
tests.
</P>
<P>
Material from each site will be sent back to the United States
o different flights to avoid any confusion. "We are treating them
as separate incidents so as not to inadvertently come to the wrong
conclusions," Kerr said.
</P>
<P>
Kerr and other FBI officials praised the "excellent
cooperation" of authorities in Kenya and Tanzania, calling the
relationship "superb."
</P>
<P>
The FBI officials said it would take at least four more weeks
to complete their examination of both bombing sites in Nairobi and
Dar es Salaam, where more than 250 people were killed, including
12 Americans, and over 5,000 injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
