<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-13 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief's Envoy Says Dialog With Iraq Will </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Prakash Shah,
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's special envoy in Iraq, said on
Thursday following his meeting with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz that dialog with Iraq would continue.
</P>
<P>
Shah told a news conference on Thursday evening that his
meeting with Aziz started at eight o'clock p.m. and lasted an
hour and a quarter.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Shah said he conveyed to Aziz a message
from Annan "which is primarily along the lines of the statement
the U.N. Secretary-General made to the Security Council on the 6th
of August."
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government announced on August 5 suspension of
cooperation with UNSCOM (the U.N. Special Commission for
disarmament in Iraq) and the International Atomic Energy Agency,
complaining that UNSCOM is pro-U.S. and attempting to prolong
sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Shah said he told Aziz that "there is a unanimous view in the
Security Council that Iraq should continue cooperation with the
United Nations and UNSCOM."
</P>
<P>
"It was this message that the secretary-general also wanted to
reinforce that the Security Council's resolutions on this matter
is quite clear, and Iraq's obligation to comply with them has been
reaffirmed in the memorandum of understanding which the
secretary-general signed with Iraq on February 23," said Shah.
</P>
<P>
Shah said Aziz wanted to convey "the Iraqi point of view, the
Iraqi concerns, the Iraqi apprehensions."
</P>
<P>
"Dialog will continue between the U.N. secretary-general's
representative and Iraqi authorities," Shah said "that is the
best description I can give at this moment," adding that Aziz
promised he would bring the message of the secretary-general to
the notice of Iraqi leadership.
</P>
<P>
Shah said he and Aziz discussed a number of things, but he
refused to go into details, saying he would report to the
secretary-general first.
</P>
<P>
Shah said he would stay in Iraq "as long as it is
necessary for the Iraqi authorities to continue this dialog,"
but he refused to predict what would happen if Iraq failed
to resume cooperation with UNSCOM. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
